<SECOND>AM-Train Crash, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0750,0665</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crews Begin Clearing Tracks From Head-On Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts one graf after 3rd graf to UPDATE with investigation
centering on accident's time. SUBS 10th graf, `Investigators
were...', with 2 grafs to UPDATE with interviews held, time
investigation. Picks up 11th graf pvs, `Investigators examined...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GREG SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALTOONA, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Firefighters put out a fire in a tanker car Monday night and authorities allowed 2,000 evacuees to return home for the first time since two freight trains crashed head-on and derailed. Police Chief <PERSON> Britt </PERSON> <PERSON> Adair </PERSON> said the fire was extinguished about 5 p.m. and the residents of northeast <LOCATION> Altoona </LOCATION> were allowed back in their homes about a half hour later. The two <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION> trains, one of which included two tanker cars carrying as much as 20,000 gallons each of volatile denatured alcohol, collided shortly before noon Saturday. Two crewmen were killed and their bodies were recovered Monday after the last fire was out. The chief investigator said Monday the probe was centering on whether one of the trains was off schedule. Fire coming from one of the cars had burned out by Monday but authorities waited to allow residents to return because of the danger of explosion from the second tanker. Flames shot up to 20 feet over the weekend but had shrunk to about 1 -LCB- feet by Monday morning. `` If it fireballed, it would kill anything within its path for a quarter mile, with devastating effects up to a half mile, and the capability of throwing shrapnel from the cars a mile and a half. That's why we evacuated a mile and a half surrounding it,'' said <PERSON> Adair </PERSON>. `` That's with one of them exploding, and we had two burning at one time.'' Bulldozers and cranes were picking through the debris and clearing the tracks of the 86 derailed cars. `` It's a situation where one of the engines rode up over the other one in a head-on collision _ went clear up in the air _ and it just completely annihilated two engines,'' the police chief said. `` There is metal and twisted debris and wheels thrown all over the place.'' He said workers had removed about 16 hopper cars by mid-afternoon Monday and that the rail line could be open to traffic by midnight if the two tankers could be removed without problems. Investigators were trying to determine how the two trains came to be on the same track. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Dobranetski </PERSON>, who heads the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> investigating team, said the two surviving crewmen and other rail workers were interviewed Monday. <PERSON> Dobranetski </PERSON> said his inquiry has not determined `` whether one train left early or whether the other was running late.'' The westbound train was to have cleared the track by 11:56 a.m., while the eastbound train was n't scheduled to leave <LOCATION> Altoona </LOCATION> until 12:01 p.m., he said. Investigators examined the controls of the wrecked eastbound train and found nothing out of order, said <PERSON> Dobranetski </PERSON>. `` The emergency brake was being applied,'' he added. The crash killed <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Peers </PERSON>, 54, of <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckingham </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, 35, of <LOCATION> Winterset </LOCATION>, both longtime employees of the railroad. Their bodies were located under the two derailed tankers, but had not been recovered earlier because of the danger of explosion. Rail officials said the eastbound <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bluffs-Chicago </ORGANIZATION> train was pulling 78 cars, while the westbound train was pulling eight cars from <LOCATION> Newton </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION>. The two employees on the eastbound train jumped to safety before the trains collided. Both victims were on the westbound train. `` He had an obviously dangerous job. He left home thousands of times and came back thousands of times,'' said Peers' son, <PERSON> Dan </PERSON>. `` This time, he did n't.'' `` They all worry about something like this happening,'' said <PERSON> Buckingham </PERSON>'s widow, <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Voy </PERSON>. `` But he was always more worried about someone else getting hurt at the crossings in a car or truck.''
</TEXT>
