<HEAD>Police Drop Plan To Protest Nelson Concert</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police officers in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and three other states dropped plans Monday to picket a <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> appearance after learning the country-and-western singer will give a concert to benefit both police and American Indian causes. `` If everything goes as planned, we probably wo n't have any demonstration,'' said <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Leavitt </PERSON>, president of the state Fraternal Order of Police. Police nationwide have been critical of <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>'s appearance last October at a benefit for <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Peltier </PERSON>, an American Indian activist serving two life sentences for the 1975 slayings of two <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents. <PERSON> Peltier </PERSON>'s supporters are raising money to pay for an appeal. The <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> FOP made plans to protest at <LOCATION> Nelson </LOCATION>'s Aug. 27 concert in <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> after <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> police said they would picket the singer concerts last weekend in <LOCATION> Warwick </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> R.I. </LOCATION>. About 800 officers from four states demonstrated at the Friday concert but canceled their Saturday protest after <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> agreed to the new benefit concert
