<HEAD>Record Heat Hits Upper Midwest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd and 4th grafs, bgng `The National...', with 3 grafs
to UPDATE with late-afternoon temperatures, which increases the
number of cities posting or tying records to 23. Also CORRECTS that
old Dubuque record was set in 1894, sted 1849; and CORRECTS that
old record in South Bend, Ind., for entire month of August was 100,
set in 1947, sted 96, set in 1944. Picks up 5th graf, `Temperatures
were...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Temperatures in the upper 90s or above 100 degrees lingered Monday across the middle <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, parts of the upper <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> and upper Great Lakes region. Temperatures of 100 degrees or above were reported as far north as southern <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> and southern <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, where high humidity was pushing heat index values up close to 120 degrees at some locations. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said 23 cities reported record highs for the date. <LOCATION> Dubuque </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, had 100 degrees, breaking the record of 98 set in 1894. Temperatures in <LOCATION> Eau </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Claire </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, reached a record 104; and in <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Crosse </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, it reached 105, smashing a 24-year-old record by 8 degrees. In <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, South Bend established an all-time record for the month of August with a 103 reading, topping the old record of 100 set on Aug. 5 and 6, 1947. <ORGANIZATION> Milwaukee </ORGANIZATION> also had all-time hottest August reading with 103. <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> had its sixth day of the season with a reading at or above 100, padding a record broken earlier in the season. Temperatures were generally in the upper 80s and lower 90s elsewhere east of the <LOCATION> Rockies </LOCATION>. Clouds were keeping readings in the 70s and lower 80s in the southern high <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, in the upper 60s to lower 80s from northeastern <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> to the northern half of <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> and in the upper 70s and lower 80s in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. Showers and thunderstorms were scattered from south-central <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> through the lower <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> to the southern <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> states. Daytime heating of a humid air mass over the nation's southeast brought afternoon showers and thunderstorms A weak weather disturbance over the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> was producing showers and thunderstorms over the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Keys </LOCATION>. Showers and thunderstorms were also developing along and ahead of a warm front curving through the northern Plains and the upper <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. Sunny and dry weather prevailed across the rest of the nation. Rainfall totals for the six hour period ended at 2 p.m. EDT included an inch at <LOCATION> Sierra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vista </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>, and a third of an inch at <LOCATION> Key </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>. Showers and thunderstorms produced up to an inch and a half of rain in central <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> Monday morning Showers and thunderstorms in south-central <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> produced an inch of rain at <LOCATION> Del </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION>, with close to 3 inches reported west of <LOCATION> Loma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alta </LOCATION>. Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 59 degrees at <LOCATION> Arcata </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, to 104 degrees at <LOCATION> Elkhart </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind </LOCATION>. The nation's low Monday morning was 38 degrees at <LOCATION> Gunnison </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>. Tuesday's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms from the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> region to the <LOCATION> northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> and across the <LOCATION> Rockies </LOCATION>, with showers and thunderstorms in northern <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, western <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Upper </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> Scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast for south-central <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> through the <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> and central Gulf Coast states to the southern <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>. High temperatures were to be in the 90s across much of the nation east of the <LOCATION> Rockies </LOCATION>, with readings near 100 degrees in the central Plains and the middle <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. Highs were forecast in the 80s in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and from the northern high Plains to <LOCATION> Upper </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, 80s and 90s in the West, with readings above 100 degrees in the <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> deserts. Highs in the 70s were forecast from the northern Rockies across <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and northern <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>.
