<SECOND>AM-US-SAfrica,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S.-Soviets meet in advance of talks on Southern Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet diplomats opened talks Sunday on southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and its racial conflicts in preparation for a new round of four-nation negotiations aimed at bringing peace to the region. Cuban, Angolan, South African and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegations are to resume talks here Tuesday on the future of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, a territory controlled by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s white-minority governmet. That session is scheduled to last three days and is the fifth publicly announced round since negotiations were started in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> last April. <PERSON> Chester </PERSON> <PERSON> Crocker </PERSON>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assistant secretary of state for <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> affairs, conferred with Soviet deputy foreign minister <PERSON> Anatoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Adamishin </PERSON> for 3 -LCB- hours Sunday at the Soviet mission. No details were given of their their talks that are set to end Monday. The four-nation conference will attempt to build on a set of principles initialed by <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> at a meeting July 13 in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. That accord commits the parties to seek a timetable for <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> to relinquish control over <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, also known as <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, under a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> plan for the territory to gain its independence. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has been battling guerrillas of the <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> for control of the territory for more than a decade. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> accuses <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s Marxist governmment of harboring and supporing the guerrillas and has frequently sent its troops into southern <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> support anti-communist guerrillas of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> for the Total Independence of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- who have been fighting the government since they were defeated in a civil war by the Marxists after <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> won independence from <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> in November 1975. <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> is participating in the talks because it has more than 40,000 military personnel in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> helping the government fight the rebels. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has said it would not grant independence to <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> until the Cuban forces are withdrawn. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has administered <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, a former German territory, since the end of World War I under a mandate by the defunct League of Nations. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> repudiated that mandate and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> rejected <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> resolutions calling for indpendence and free elections in the territory. <PERSON> Crocker </PERSON> on July 20 called the agreement on principles an important step but said `` there are a great many hard and difficult compromises to be achieved.'' Previous rounds in the talks included sessions in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and a meeting of top military officers from the four sides in the <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Verde </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>.
