<HEAD>Dukakis Seeing Benefits _ and Disadvantages _ of Campaign Life</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has drawn some large crowds in the two campaign swings he's taken since leaving <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> as the Democratic presidential nominee. Invariably, he has attracted protesters too. At virtually every stop in his campaign travels, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has been confronted by demonstrators, sometimes numbering no more than a dozen, but always vocal. Most carry signs and chant slogans objecting to the right of women to have abortions. Often mixed with them are signs supporting Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, and there are occasional signs attacking <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' record in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, such as the one in <LOCATION> Sturtevant </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, last week that said: `` <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the criminal's choice, go home.'' It referred to the program, since modified, allowing prison furloughs for some convicted murderers in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. The presence of anti-abortion protesters recalls the campaign in 1984 of vice presidential nominee <PERSON> Geraldine </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferraro </PERSON>, who faced similar demonstrations at many speeches. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign staffers, many of whom are veterans of the Mondale-Ferraro effort, say they and their candidate are not bothered or surprised by the protesters. `` We expect them at every event,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' senior issues adviser who travels with the candidate The largest gathering, numbering 100 or more, confronted <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> as he went to church on Sunday a week ago in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Secaucus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, last week, the dozen or so protesters positioned themselves so close behind the stage that their chants were picked up by the public address system _ and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had to walk right by them as he left. In <PERSON> Sturtevant </PERSON> a day later, a larger group chanted slogans throughout his speech, and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> appeared to have been put off his stride by the distraction. Was he rattled? `` Rattled? I did n't feel rattled. Did I look rattled? I did n't feel rattled Did I look rattled? Terribly rattled? `` Let me tell you, If you went through the kind of governorship I went through in the first four years as governor of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, that's a day at the beach,'' added <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. He was turned out of office after that turbulent first term, in 1978, then regained it four years later.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' Greek heritage and sometimes bland style prompted humorist <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> to pin the name `` Zorba the clerk'' on <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. Last week in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> found a phrase on a supporter's placard that he seemed to like better. `` Zeus on the loose,'' it said, in reference to the supreme deity of the ancient Greeks. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> picked that one out of the crowd as he stood on the platform beginning his speech. `` I do n't know what that means,'' he told the audience. But he said he would tell his wife <PERSON> Kitty </PERSON> about it.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Since leaving <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has rarely failed to mention to audiences that 25-year-old snow blower of his. It was first displayed to the nation by cousin <PERSON> Olympia </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the actress, in a campaign film aired as part of the Democratic National Convention. It has become, he said, a symbol of the efficient frugality he embodies. Mentioning the snow blower sometimes seemed a bit out of place with the setting as he campaigned in 90 degree and 100 degree temperatures, such as inside the hot <LOCATION> Dorton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arena </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Raleigh </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, on Saturday. But he did _ and noted that he not only still has the machine, he still has its owners manual.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 It may not be at the top of most voters' lists of concerns in a president, but journalists always want to know what a new president has in mind for frequency of news conferences. When asked that question in local television interviews in <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said, `` I would expect two, three, four times a week I would be meeting with the press, taking questions.''
