<HEAD>Rapid City Fire Nearly Out, Fires Slow In Yellowstone</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to UPDATE with Rapid City fire controlled,
add Oregon to list of states. Picks up 3rd graf pvs. Inserts one
graf after 8th graf ``Elsewhere in...' with details. Subs last 2
grafs with 3 grafs to UPDATE Idaho fire and add detail on Oregon
fire.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Yellowstone National Park officials re-opened areas of the park Sunday that had been closed because of forest fires, and firefighters used hand tools to choke the last embers of a controlled fire that destroyed 15 homes at Rapid City, S.D. Crews battled at least four new blazes in two national forests in <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>, a wilderness fire forced evacuation of a ranger station in <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, and firefighters also were at work in the forests of <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Fire activity in <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> declined Sunday, said Costa Dillon, fire information officer. That allowed officials to re-open the park's south entrance north of <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wyo. </LOCATION>, closed one week ago by the 10,100-acre Shoshone fire and the 10,600-acre Red fire. Officials also re-opened the park's <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Thumb </LOCATION> area Sunday, closed Saturday when firefighters started controlled burns to remove fuels before the Shoshone fire, which jumped the road from the southern entrance, could reach the area. A controlled burn on the eastern and northeastern edge of the 11,300-acre North Fork fire, which at one point was six miles from the tourist complex at Old Faithful geyser, had worked as planned and flames headed north away from the geyser Sunday, <PERSON> Dillon </PERSON> said. Firefighters completed a containment line around 30 percent of the fire and hoped for full containment by Wednesday, he added. Because the fire was caused by man rather than lightning, firefighters will attempt to control it. The largest fire in the park, the 68,035-acre Clover Mist, did not grow significantly during the weekend, <PERSON> Dillon </PERSON> said. Elsewhere in <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>, two new fires in the <ORGANIZATION> Bighorn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> kept firefighters busy, and crews in the <ORGANIZATION> Targhee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> fought two lightning-caused blazes. The largest had covered 1,260 acres on Medicine Mountain in the Big Horn. A timber fire that burned 3,840 acres in the <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> on the western edge of <ORGANIZATION> Rapid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> over six days was declared controlled Sunday night, as was a 35-acre fire that broke out nearby Saturday. A fire is considered controlled when it is reduced to smoldering patches. <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Waxler </PERSON>, a fire information officer, said about 584 firefighters were at the fire Sunday morning, about half the number there 24 hours earlier. The remaining firefighters worked from the fire line to the center of the burned area with hand tools and other equipment, <PERSON> Waxler </PERSON> said. `` Basically, they're doing things like extinguishing embers and turning over logs to make sure that things are out,'' she said. The Rock Creek fire in the Selway-Bitterroot Wilderness Area of southwestern <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> jumped fire lines and covered about 3,000 acres Sunday, said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kendley </PERSON>, fire information officer at the <ORGANIZATION> Inter-Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dispatch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Helena </LOCATION>. Although it was in a wilderness area, the fire was being fought because it was man-caused. Late Saturday, smoke from the fire could be seen in <LOCATION> Helena </LOCATION>, more than 100 miles away, he said. In northwestern <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, 10 to 15 people were evacuated from a remote ranger station in the <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> Wilderness Area when the Gates fire spread to about 8,000 acres, <PERSON> Kendley </PERSON> said. `` That fire increased 2,000 to 3,000 acres in size'' on Saturday, <PERSON> Kendley </PERSON> said. `` The buildings -LRB- at the station -RRB- have been covered with fireproof tarps, a gravity-feed sprinkler system has been installed on a nearby ridge and personnel and livestock have been evacuated from the station.'' Also in the <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Canyon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> blaze had grown to 15,000 acres Sunday, he said. In <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, ground crews cleared landing areas for helicopters around the 5,000-acre <PERSON> Willis </PERSON> <PERSON> Gulch </PERSON> fire so weary firefighters can be flown back and forth from the remote fire line in the <ORGANIZATION> Boise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION>. The heliports cut the walk for firefighters from four miles to about a half mile. Containment was expected Monday evening, and by late Sunday a containment line had been thrown around 90 percent of the fire's 10-mile perimeter, forest officials said Firefighters in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> continued work Sunday on the 3,600-acre <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> fire along the crest of the <LOCATION> Cascades </LOCATION>, about 12 miles northeast of Mount Rainier National Park, and a smaller burn in the Cascade foothills. A 75-acre fire broke out late Saturday in the <ORGANIZATION> Mount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and and a lightning storm sparked nearly 70 small fires in southern <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, forest spokeswomen said.
