<FIRST>r i PM-TheEiger Bjt   08-01 0727</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-The Eiger, Bjt,0755</SECOND>
<HEAD>Climber Recalls Travails of Eiger's North Face 50 Years Later</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA WATSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRINDELWALD, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gazing up at the sheer limestone north face of the Eiger, mountaineer <PERSON> Heinrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrer </PERSON> reminisced about the climb 50 years ago that changed his life. In July 1938, he and three other climbers became the first to scale the daunting 5,940-foot wall in the heart of the <LOCATION> Swiss </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alps </LOCATION> that is considered <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s greatest challenge to mountaineers. `` We were never afraid. We never had any idea of returning or giving up'' despite difficulties during the four-day adventure, the 76-year-old <PERSON> Harrer </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in a recent interview. Nine people had already died on the wall before <PERSON> Harrer </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fritz </PERSON> <PERSON> Kasparek </PERSON>, both Austrians, and <PERSON> Andreas </PERSON> <PERSON> Heckmair </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ludwig </PERSON> <PERSON> Voerg </PERSON>, both Germans, set out before dawn one morning to conquer the last virgin face of the <LOCATION> Alps </LOCATION>. Because of the danger, authorities had outlawed attempts to climb the north face. But the four defied the ban. `` We climbed the wall secretly,'' said <PERSON> Harrer </PERSON>, sitting in an Alpine meadow with a dramatic view of the north face. `` When we came down after four days, we were surprised to find out that the whole world knew about it.'' It turned out that observers had spotted them. <PERSON> Harrer </PERSON> recently returned to <LOCATION> Grindelwald </LOCATION>, a village at the base of the Eiger, for a weekend celebration with hundreds of other mountaineers and fans on the anniversary of the climb. Another guest of honor was 82-year-old Heckmair. <PERSON> Kasparek </PERSON> and <PERSON> Voerg </PERSON> are both dead. The Eiger north face, which juts up almost vertically above <LOCATION> Grindelwald </LOCATION>, lived up to its reputation that celebration weekend. An English climber trying to scale it fell and sustained serious head injuries, but was rescued alive by helicopter. Just Saturday, a 26-year-old South Korean was killed in a 3,300-foot fall as he tried to scale the Eiger's north face, the <ORGANIZATION> Swiss </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rescue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said. The recent helicopter rescue recalled the most dramatic rescue from the Eiger, the first time a climber was rescued alive. In 1957, before helicopters were used, Italian <PERSON> Claudio </PERSON> <PERSON> Corti </PERSON> was saved at an icy patch three-quarters of the way up the wall. But his countryman <PERSON> Stefano </PERSON> <PERSON> Longhi </PERSON> froze to death and his body hung from his rope, out of reach of rescuers, for two years. It was only when winches were put in place in 1959 that the corpse could be retrieved. <PERSON> Harrer </PERSON> said that after 50 years, public interest in the Eiger and the historic first climb has actually increased. `` This wall has developed a certain kind of charisma, a mythical attraction,'' he says. Since the 1938 climb, about 700 mountaineers have successfully ascended the wall using various routes to get to the peak 13,101 feet above sea level. <PERSON> Harrer </PERSON> said the fact that so many have climbed the north face does not diminish the challenge. `` Fifty people have died on that wall, which proves that the wall has n't become easier,'' he said. But he added, `` it has become easier provided you are an expert, provided you are equipped properly, provided you have prepared this climb and chosen the proper time to do it.'' In a book he wrote about his ascent, <PERSON> Harrer </PERSON> tells how he and his partners waited for days, watching the weather around the Eiger, before picking the best moment to begin their climb. The climbers nourished themselves mostly with hot tea and cocoa. <PERSON> Harrer </PERSON> said his only solid food during the climb was a slice of bread and butter that his mother had given him 14 days earlier, as he left home after taking his university exams. `` I did n't tell her where I was going, just that I was going climbing,'' he said. The most tense moments of the 1938 climb came on the third day, when the mountaineers clung to the nearly vertical face to withstand avalanches, hailstorms and snowstorms. `` This is part of the Eiger north wall,'' <PERSON> Harrer </PERSON> said. He said he was not afraid. `` Once you start action, you are on the wall, you never think of any danger.'' Yet he said that before reaching the wall, one always has `` some thoughts that you could return now, it is not too late.'' `` But it's very simple. If you do n't overcome fear, you will never be prepared to do something exceptional.''
</TEXT>
