in July 1982. There have been reports that they were killed, and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has been seeking word on them. After arriving in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> on Sunday, The Rev. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> told reporters he hoped his mission to <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> had `` made a contribution towards the overall picture, which I hope will lead towards the release of all the hostages.'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, Anglican bishop in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> region, went at the request of his church's head, Archbishop of Canterbury <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON>. He said he spoke in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> to leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> Maronite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> and the Armenian church, who `` promised to make inquiries. `` It's very important to us when we are talking to the Iranians ... to show them that we are concerned about their missing people as well as ours,'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> told reporters. <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON> aide <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyttle </PERSON> said <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> was `` well guarded'' during his visit and did not venture out of the Christian part of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Waite </PERSON> disappeared Jan. 20, 1987, while seeking the release of American hostages in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. The longest-held hostage is <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, chief <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> correspondent for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, who was abducted March 16, 1985.
