<FIRST>r a PM-WritersStrike     08-01 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Writers Strike,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Producers: `We've Hit the Brick Wall'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Talks to end the 22-week scriptwriters strike have `` hit a brick wall,'' according to the producers' top negotiator who is urging strikers to cross picket lines and end the industry's second-longest walkout. `` We will get our production on schedule any way we can,'' <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Counter </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, president the <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Picture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Producers </ORGANIZATION>, said at a news conference Sunday. `` What individual writers choose to do is up to them.'' A union spokeswoman predicted that strikers would remain steadfast. `` To encourage writers to come back to work is an unfortunate retrenchment at a time when both sides should resume negotiation and settle this dispute,'' said spokeswoman <PERSON> Cheryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhoden </PERSON>. The negotiations deadlocked Saturday after an 11-hour session. `` We've simply gotten to the end of the road, and we've hit a brick wall,'' <PERSON> Counter </PERSON> said of the 217-member alliance. `` We will redouble our efforts to produce as many programs as possible.'' The major unresolved issue is how much the writers should get from sale of TV shows and movies abroad and from domestic TV reruns. The strike, which began March 7, has left the fall television season in chaos and has led to financial hardship for many of the <ORGANIZATION> Writers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>'s 9,000 members, as well as entertainment-related industries. Counter said production companies belonging to the alliance would welcome strike-breaking union members and likely would offer financial protection against any union reprisal. Guild officials have said writers who go back to work risk fines of up to 110 percent of their compensation from the producers and expulsion from the union. About 50 guild members, meanwhile, singled out <ORGANIZATION> Walt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studios </ORGANIZATION> on Sunday by picketing movie theaters in <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Westwood </LOCATION> showing the hit <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> film `` Who Framed <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabbit </PERSON>.'' The demonstrators blamed Disney for blocking a tentative settlement with the alliance, and held signs and passed out fliers saying `` Who framed the writers guild?'' and `` <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Mouse </PERSON> is stealing from our kids.'' <PERSON> Rhoden </PERSON> called the demonstrations `` public outrage pickets,'' and said more would be planned this week here and in other parts of the country. She called prospects of a fall TV season `` doubtful and improbable. They may put a few shows on the air, but it will not be a full schedule.'' The strike is only a week short of the entertainment's industry's longest _ a 23-week walkout by the guild in 1960 That strike won writers payments for television reruns. Also Sunday, Counter and <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, chairman of the basic crafts unions, issued a joint statement Sunday saying the alliance and behind-the-scenes workers agreed to extend their contracts on a day-to-day basis. Those contracts were to have expired at midnight. `` The parties will resume discussions on Wednesday ... with the expectation of negotiating to conclusion,'' the statement said.
