<FIRST>r w PM-PresidentialTransition     08-01 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Presidential Transition,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heading Off Foreign Policy Squabbles: Experts Tell How</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new president should move quickly to fill foreign policy posts and make clear immediately that his secretary of state is his `` one principal lieutenant'' in foreign affairs, a report on presidential transition recommends. The report noted that Presidents <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>, <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> and <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> `` all found their administrations involved early in internal disputes between the national security adviser and the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>.'' The report never mentioned the Iran-Contra affair, which came to light in President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s second term. But it said `` recent events'' have demonstrated the need for a new president to tell his national security adviser `` at the start precisely what role and responsibilities'' he and his staff should assume, `` including their relations with the secretary of state. `` Coherence and consistency in foreign policy are best served if the president has only one principal lieutenant in that area, the secretary of state.'' The report, entitled `` Transferring Responsibility: The Dangers of Transition,'' was released by the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burkett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Miller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> of Public Affairs at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION>. The study was the work of a Commission On Presidential Transitions and Foreign Policy headed by former secretaries of state <PERSON> Cyrus </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vance </PERSON> and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>. The commission included members of every post-war presidential transition, from the <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt-Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> changeover to that of <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Rogers-Vance </ORGANIZATION> commission recommended: _ Key foreign policy officials should be selected promptly by a new administration, with Cabinet officers chosen within four weeks of the election and sub-Cabinet positions filled within 10 weeks The process often takes longer, the report said, because of political considerations in the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. _ Key presidential foreign policy documents should be reproduced for the incoming president `` We know of no large institution other than the White House in which, when a change of leadership occurs, many of the files relevant to continuing policy decisions are packed up and taken away by the departing top official,'' the report said. _ The <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> should be restored as the `` institutional memory'' of the president's office and the number of political appointees at the top of <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> should be reduced _ Pre-inaugural meetings between representatives of the incoming administration and foreign diplomats and leaders should be sharply limited _ Each presidential candidate should begin building a pool of potential foreign policy appointees immediately after the political party conventions, and use small task forces rather than large transition teams The report said that during a presidential campaign, candidates should be careful `` in the number and scope of promises they make in the foreign policy field. Some political promises which bring success in the election may produce failure in office.'' Once in office, a new president should be careful not to `` politicize the career services,'' the report said. New administrations are often `` distrustful of bureaucrats'' and only slowly do they learn how heavily they can rely on the professionalism of foreign service officers and members of the other career services,'' the report said.
</TEXT>
