<FIRST>r a PM-HashHouseHarriers     08-01 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hash House Harriers,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hashing: A Running Game Played From Malaysia to Maine</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AD1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY HARKAVY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRYANT POND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A pack of runners darted through the woods, bushwhacked up and down thicket-choked slopes, dashed along railroad tracks and abandoned roads, forded knee-deep streams and slogged through thigh-high mud. They closed out the day with beer, a barbecue and good fellowship. Born in the rubber plantations and jungles of east <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> in an era when the sun never set on the British empire, the sport known as hashing has made its way halfway around the world to <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, where one devotee is writing a book about it. Hashing, a non-competitive form of cross-country running that traces its roots to the game of hare and hounds, is enjoyed by roughly 50,000 participants in more than 700 clubs in 124 countries from <LOCATION> Andorra </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>. `` It's a way to get a little exercise and a little sociability,'' said freelance writer <PERSON> Alice </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> of <PERSON> Hallowell </PERSON>, founder of the <ORGANIZATION> Hallowell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hash </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harriers </ORGANIZATION>, one of about 80 clubs in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> leads with 16. For her research on her forthcoming book, <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> was recently in <LOCATION> Bali </LOCATION>, site of the 1988 Interhash, known as the biennial Olympics of hashing, and in <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION> for the the 50th anniversary celebration of the founding of the original Hash House Harriers, known affectionately as `` the mother hash.'' The group was founded at a Kuala Lumpur club by British soldiers and expatriate businessmen who ran through the jungle to work up a thirst. It selected the name from the institutional quality of the club's food. At a midsummer hash that began at her lakefront cottage here, <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> briefed newcomers on the rules. Runners designated as hares set the course in advance, marking it with flour; they are the only ones who know where it will lead. At various points, hares draw circles indicating checkpoints from which several possible routes fan out in different directions. All but one are false trails that end with a marker telling the runner to return to the checkpoint and try again. The runner who finally discovers the right trail shouts `` I'm on! or `` On-on!'' The hares who follow the pack to keep track of stragglers sound a horn, and all run toward the next checkpoint to restart the process. The search for the correct trail provides time for slower runners to catch up with those up front. `` It takes away a lot of the ego trip involved with track and other competitive racing,'' said <PERSON> Noel </PERSON> <PERSON> Mount </PERSON>, an Irish-born former rugby player who was one of the two dozen <PERSON> Hallowell </PERSON> hashers to run the nearly six-mile course. `` You get ahead, but then you take the wrong trail and that brings you back with everyone else.'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>'s husband, <PERSON> Wick </PERSON>, along with summer neighbors <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> Greeves </PERSON> and <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Engelman </PERSON>, reconnoitered the area the previous evening and spent three hours that morning laying out the route and marking it with 10 pounds of flour. In the tropics, hares use paper rather than flour to leave their marks. <PERSON> Greeves </PERSON>, a resident of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, introduced the <ORGANIZATION> Johnsons </ORGANIZATION> to hashing two years ago. While on a visit to <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Wick </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> was invited by <PERSON> Greeves </PERSON> to participate in an all-male hash. He returned exhausted but enthusiastic, telling his wife, a recreational runner, that this was a sport she would love. Upon her return home that summer, <PERSON> Alice </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> rounded up a group of friends and neighbors from <PERSON> Hallowell </PERSON>, just outside <LOCATION> Augusta </LOCATION>, and organized the area's first hash. `` The trick is getting the right people at the beginning. It has to be people who do n't take themselves too seriously,'' she said. `` Most are runners, but it is definitely not a requirement. You just have to be fit enough to run approximately six miles _ with stops.''
</TEXT>
