<HEAD>Explosion Causes Army Barracks To Collapse</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with Scotland Yard saying at least one dead, suspect
device found in car, firefighters withdrawn from area. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An explosion caused a two-story army barracks in north <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to collapse early Monday, killing at least one person and injuring at least seven, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> Yard said. Part of the Inglis barracks, which houses members of the Women's <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>., caught fire, <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brigade </ORGANIZATION> officials <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said an army disposal unit was inspecting a `` suspect device'' found in a car in a parking lot adjacent to the barracks in the <LOCATION> Mill </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> neighborhood. It said firefighters were withdrawn from the area. The cause of the explosion was not immediately known. <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> radio had reported that two people died and 20 were trapped at the <PERSON> Inglis </PERSON> barracks in the <LOCATION> Mill </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> neighborhood. Press Association, the domestic British news agency, reported one dead and eight injured in the explosion, which occurred about 7 a.m. -LRB- 2 a.m. EDT -RRB-. The <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> said the barracks also is used as an army postal and courier depot. <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> Ambulance said the injured were taken to two hospitals. `` One of the injured is in a critical state with back and leg injuries,'' said an ambulance spokesman, speaking anonymously in keeping with British custom. The barracks are located in Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s parliamentary constituency
