<FIRST>r i PM-Gulf-Mines     08-01 0771</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gulf-Mines,0797</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gulf Still Has `Couple of Hundred' Mines, Officers Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABOARD USS CONQUEST IN THE PERSIAN GULF (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 This old <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> mine sweeper and five others like it may remain in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> until an estimated `` couple of hundred'' mines still lurking in the waters are found and destroyed, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officers say. While a cease-fire in the Iraq-Iran war would probably keep new mines from being laid, those already deployed could pose a danger to shipping for years to come unless cleaned up. The task falls to ships like the creaky, 800-ton Conquest, whose crew works these days in 130-degree deck temperatures, using a submersible robot to locate mines and trailing gear to cut the cables that moor them to the seabed. When a submerged mine shows up on the sonar screen, divers are guided to the spot and attach explosives, which are detonated by time fuse or remote control. Capt. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, `` commodore'' of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> mine-sweeping force, would not predict how long the tedious and dangerous job of clearing the gulf of mines might require. `` We're not going to do it in a week or two weeks,'' he said in an interview. `` It's going to take a lot longer than that.'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said this could mean some or all of the six <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> mine sweepers in the gulf might be excluded from a force cutback promised by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials when and if <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> formally agree to a truce in their 8-year-old war. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, which is blamed for laying most of the mines in the gulf, announced July 18 that it would join <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> in accepting a year-old <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> cease-fire resolution. The wooden-hulled <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> mine sweepers, all built in the early 1950s but updated for gulf duty with modern sonar, navigation and mine-hunting gear, comprise about a third of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> naval force now in the gulf. Their `` mothership'' is the amphibious landing ship <LOCATION> Dubuque </LOCATION>, which also carries about 400 Marines and eight helicopters. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military sources in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> say the six aging mine sweepers might possibly be given to a gulf Arab state rather than returned to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The navy has 15 other mine sweepers of similar vintage, and is building 31 new, state-of-the-art ships for hunting mines. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said he had `` no firsthand knowledge'' of such a plan, but noted that scores of former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships are now sailing with other navies. He conceded it could take years before the gulf is free of mines, if ever. Mines laid in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> during World War II were still being recovered as recently as 1980, he said. The mine threat had a major role in prompting the naval buildup by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and five European navies in the gulf a year ago. In addition to the six <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> craft, which arrived in November, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> sent anti-mine forces. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> also has ships capable of mine-sweeping in the waterway. European forces were later cut back, and two remaining Belgian and Dutch mine-hunters combined with three British ships under <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> command. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> records indicate at least 10 vessels have hit mines in the gulf since the Soviet tanker Marshal <PERSON> Chuikov </PERSON> was damaged off <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> on May 16, 1987. Among later victims were the U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti supertanker <LOCATION> Bridgeton </LOCATION>, the American frigate <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, an offshore supply vessel sunk with six killed and an ocean survey ship with four lost. After the <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> narrowly escaped destruction in the central gulf on April 14, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> searchers found three more mines in those waters. Officers said all were clean of marine growth, indicating they were newly laid, and one bore the letters `` USA'' in white paint. The mines, of a 1908 Russian type, were identical with those found aboard the captured Iranian minelayer <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> Ajr in September, they said. Overall, some 80 mines have been found in the past year, according to available records. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said `` everybody has found some.'' The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> found 52, the latest in May. The British and French each have found more than a dozen. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said the estimated `` couple of hundred'' mines still in the gulf are concentrated in certain areas, including waters just south of <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and an area of the northern gulf near Iranian-held <LOCATION> Farsi </LOCATION> island. The mines off <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, believed laid by both sides, are a special threat because they break lose in rough weather and drift to the Arab side of the gulf. Several vessels have struck these renegade `` floaters'' off <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bahrain </LOCATION>.
