<HEAD>China Reportedly Refusing to Allow Pol Pot Leave The Country</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities in <LOCATION> Bejing </LOCATION> are refusing to allow former <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> ruler <PERSON> Pol </PERSON> <PERSON> Pot </PERSON> to leave <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, where the leader of the murderous <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> regime is hospitalized for unspecified treatment, a magazine reported. The August edition of the Chinese-language <ORGANIZATION> Cheng </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ming </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION>, seen today, also said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> will offer political asylum to <PERSON> Pol </PERSON> <PERSON> Pot </PERSON>. While <PERSON> Pol </PERSON> <PERSON> Pot </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> ruled <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> from 1975-78, hundreds of thousands of people died in vast slave-labor camps and execution chambers as the government attempted to turn the country into a primitive agrarian society. Vietnamese forces drove the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> into the mountain jungles of western <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> and installed the current <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION> government in early 1979. <PERSON> Pol </PERSON> <PERSON> Pot </PERSON> has not been seen by outsiders in recent years and has been reported to suffer from various ailments that sent him for treatment to <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Cheng </PERSON> <PERSON> Ming </PERSON>, in a brief report about <PERSON> Pol </PERSON> <PERSON> Pot </PERSON>, said he was being treated at an unidentified <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> hospital. The China-watching magazine said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> had reached a tacit agreement with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to stop supplying military aid to <PERSON> Pol </PERSON> <PER