<HEAD>Mass Resignation Raises Questions About Italy's War on Mafia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To CLARIFY that resigning magistrates comprised `anti-Mafia
pool' and ADD details on heroin network, SUB grafs 6-8, `Falcone,
48 ... crime trial.' Picks up 9th graf, `The so-called ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As the nation's top Mafia investigator, <PERSON> Giovanni </PERSON> <PERSON> Falcone </PERSON> symbolized a new generation of brave, activist judges dedicated to ending the reign of organized crime in <LOCATION> Sicily </LOCATION>. Now, he and eight fellow investigating magistrates have resigned, spurring questions about the depth of the government's commitment to fighting the Mafia All nine had played a prominent role in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s largest Mafia trial. In stepping down with the others on Saturday, <PERSON> Falcone </PERSON> said he wanted to be able to freely testify before a judicial panel looking into the government's anti-Mafia effort. He also suggested there was something profoundly wrong with the war on organized crime. Following reports that members of <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s dominant political party had in an unrelated case arranged payment of a ransom to underworld figures, the resignations shocked Italians and prompted criticism of the government. `` The judges and all the others that have risked their lives fighting the Mafia have felt increasingly abandoned by the state,'' the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Corriere </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> della </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sera </ORGANIZATION> said in a front-page editorial on Sunday. <PERSON> Falcone </PERSON>, 48, and the other eight resigning investigators had together comprised a special `` anti-Mafia pool,'' which was formed after the 1983 assassination of the chief investigating magistrate in <LOCATION> Palermo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sicily </LOCATION>'s capital. The team, led by <PERSON> Falcone </PERSON>, pushed Italian law to its limit, examining bank records of alleged Mafiosi and ordering sweeping arrests. It was the dapper, mustachioed <PERSON> Falcone </PERSON> who persuaded mob figure <PERSON> Tommaso </PERSON> <PERSON> Buscetta </PERSON> to detail the structure of the Mafia and how it shipped heroin from <LOCATION> Sicily </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, a breakthrough that led to the nation's huge organized crime trial. The so-called maxi-trial ended in December with convictions of 338 Mafiosi, including 19 reputed members of the <ORGANIZATION> Cosa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nostra </ORGANIZATION>'s leadership commission Since the trial, however, the anti-Mafia pool has been stymied by its new director, chaos in the police force and government indifference, according to prominent Sicilian prosecutor <PERSON> Paolo </PERSON> <PERSON> Borsellino </PERSON>. <PERSON> Borsellino </PERSON>'s declarations to journalists two weeks ago prompted President <PERSON> Francesco </PERSON> <PERSON> Cossiga </PERSON> to order investigations by the ministries of <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Magistrates </ORGANIZATION>, which oversees judges. As the judges' body began hearings in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> on Saturday, <PERSON> Falcone </PERSON> and his colleagues submitted their resignations and asked for transfers. `` That which I had feared could happen unfortunately happened,'' <PERSON> Falcone </PERSON> wrote. `` The investigations into the Mafia have been obstructed and -LRB- the anti-Mafia pool -RRB- ... is now stalled.'' Another investigator who resigned, <PERSON> Giuseppe </PERSON> <PERSON> Di </PERSON> <PERSON> Lello </PERSON>, charged: `` The inattention of the government is palpable in the disorganization of the investigating offices.'' <PERSON> Falcone </PERSON> did not elaborate on how or why the investigations may have slowed. But he said his views on prosecuting the Mafia `` diverge radically'' from those of the chief investigating magistrate, <PERSON> Antonino </PERSON> <PERSON> Meli </PERSON>. <PERSON> Meli </PERSON> was appointed in February over the objections of <PERSON> Falcone </PERSON> and others, who said he had no experience in Mafia probes. <PERSON> Borsellino </PERSON>, a former member of the anti-Mafia pool, told reporters that <PERSON> Meli </PERSON> had removed <PERSON> Falcone </PERSON> as chief of major anti-Mafia cases. <PERSON> Meli </PERSON> also divided the anti-Mafia work load among all investigators, regardless of whether they were specialists, <PERSON> Borsellino </PERSON> said, reverting to the system followed before the pool was created. `` There have been serious attempts by the office of investigations and the prosecutor of the republic of <LOCATION> Palermo </LOCATION> to definitively dismantle the anti-Mafia pool,'' he said. <PERSON> Meli </PERSON> responded: `` The pool has not been destroyed, as <PERSON> Borsellino </PERSON> says, and if anything it has been enlarged with the addition of other judges.'' Saturday's resignations prompted expressions of concern from Italian politicians about the state of the war on the Mafia. `` There is a problem of management and administration of men; of the types of judges; and it is more than a guess to think that the difficulties have been exacerbated by the inopportune handling of this government,'' said <PERSON> Virginio </PERSON> <PERSON> Rognoni </PERSON> of the dominant <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> party who heads the justice commission in the Chamber of Deputies. Last Thursday, an investigating judge released a report saying some <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> helped gain the release of a kidnapped colleague in 1981 by arranging ransoms for the <ORGANIZATION> Neopolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mafia </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brigade </ORGANIZATION> leftist terrorists. Among those who may have been involved was <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Gava </PERSON>, the current interior minister, the report said. <PERSON> Gava </PERSON> denied the charge. `` Today, we expected the resignation of Interior Minister <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Gava </PERSON>,'' the Communist newspaper <ORGANIZATION> L'Unita </ORGANIZATION> said in a front-page editorial Sunday headlined `` Honest Men and an Arrogant Government.'' `` <PERSON> Gava </PERSON> stays and <PERSON> Falcone </PERSON> leaves; it is not a good day for <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>.''
