<HEAD>Emigration At Eight-Year High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Jewish emigration from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> reached a new eight-year-high in July with a total of 1,639 allowed to leave the country, the agency involved in their resettlement said today. The total represented the seventh straight monthly rise in the number of arrivals at the <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, transit center, the Geneva-based <ORGANIZATION> Intergovermental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Migration </ORGANIZATION> said. Only 930 people opted for new homes in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, well below the recent average, the committee said. Last month's figure compared with 1,767 who left the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in June 1980, and brought to 7,656 the number of Jews emigrating in the first seven months of the year, the committee said. The largest official exodus _ 51,330 _ was recorded in 1979 before the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> intervention in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> chilled East-West relations. Nearly 270,000 Soviet Jews have emigrated since the resettlement program began in 1971.
