<HEAD>More Murder And Assault Cases; 1,200 Officers Fired After
Corruption Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Violent crime in the Soviet capital is down overall but murders, assaults and juvenile crime are on the rise and authorities probing police corruption have fired about 1,200 people, an official said. `` We do n't hide that fact that in our ranks, there are bribe-takers, money-grubbers, common criminals in police uniform,'' said Lt. Gen. P.S. <PERSON> Bogdanov </PERSON>, chief of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION>, which controls police affairs. `` But we will not stop until our ranks have been cleansed,'' <PERSON> Bogdanov </PERSON> told a recent news conference in remarks published Sunday by <ORGANIZATION> Komsomolskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pravda </ORGANIZATION>, the national youth daily. He said that as a result of investigations in the first half of 1988, about 1,200 Internal Affairs employees in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> were fired. The official said that in the first six months of 1988, there was a rise in murder, assault with intent to kill and assault resulting in serious injury, compared to the same period last year. The newspaper report gave no specific figures or reasons for the change. <PERSON> Bogdanov </PERSON> said, however, that the number of all crimes registered in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> declined by 9.6 percent compared to 1987. Violent crime _ excluding murder and assault _ dropped by 4.2 percent, he said. He did not give the actual number of crimes registered. In the first six months of 1988, Muscovites aged 18 and younger committed 25.6 percent of the crimes in the city, while juvenile crime accounted for 22.6 percent of the city's unlawful acts during the same period in 1987, the police general said. The juvenile crimes included robbery, rape, joyriding in someone else's car and apartment break-ins, he said. <PERSON> Bogdanov </PERSON> said his ministry will continue to clean out corruption in police ranks, a process begun more than a year ago under the reforms of Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
