<HEAD>Heat Bakes Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 August got off to a blistering start in many central and eastern states with unusually high temperatures early today, following a record-setting day of triple-digit heat in six Midwestern states. A high pressure system was centered over southeast <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> on Sunday night, keeping much of the warmer air across the central and eastern parts of the nation and bringing comparatively cooler temperatures to the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> and northern Plateau regions. Temperatures early this morning were very warm across much of the nation with readings in the 70s along much of the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> into the southeast states and parts of the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>; and in the 80s across the central and southern Plains into the middle <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> and from southern <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> through much of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> into southeast <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>. Showers and thunderstorms were developing early this morning across central and southern parts of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>. Other showers and thunderstorms were moving across eastern parts of upper <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, as well as the <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> coast and into northern parts of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, rain flooded low-lying roadways at Nags Head and <LOCATION> Collington </LOCATION>. More than 2 inches of rain drenched <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hanover </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, early this morning. Thunderstorms abated late Sunday night and early this morning over the central and southern parts of the <LOCATION> Rockies </LOCATION>. But heavy rain was reported Sunday afternoon at <LOCATION> Prescott </LOCATION>, <L