<SECOND>PM-China-Military,0662</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ranks Restored In Chinese Army</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Chinese military celebrated its 61st anniversary today by restoring a ranking system in a move seen as critical to its efforts to develop a modern fighting force. In related developments Saturday, the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> bestowed medals on thousands of veterans and announced more than 100,000 soldiers would be transferred to a new civilian staff. Western military analysts in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and the official <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> media said the moves were connected to reforms aimed at modernizing <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s armed forces and ridding it of the leftist influences. The analysts, who spoke on condition of anonymity, also said the ranking system was designed to raise the morale of the army, which since 1978 has seen many of its factories converted to civilian use and its troop strength and share of the state budget slashed. <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-tung </PERSON> abolished military ranks 23 years ago as part of his attempt to create a classless society. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> then ascribed to a fighting philosophy called `` people's war,'' which envisaged an all-out war fought by a huge peasant army. Since <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> began its economic reforms in 1978, it has moved to create a professional army with top-notch military equipment. Western analysts today said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s poor showing in its brief war with <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> in 1979 also did much to convince military leaders of the necessity of a strict ranking system. In addition, the trouble with <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> on the border and over islands in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> has led the Chinese to believe future conflicts will not be an all-out war but `` geographically contained battles that necessitate a rapid deployment force of highly trained soldiers,'' said one diplomat. `` These kinds of units need a strict command structure, with a clear delineation as to who is giving and who is receiving the orders,'' he said. `` Before today they did n't have that.'' Friday's issue of the People's Daily -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Renmin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ribao </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- said the move to transfer 100,000 soldiers to civilian status was part of a program to cut the number of `` officials'' in the army. `` The ratio of officials to soldiers is lopsided,'' it said. `` They are too many officers and many of them are too old.'' Apart from strategic issues, analysts said the ranking system and the awarding of medals were undertaken to raise morale in the People's <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. Since 1978, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> had reduced the army from 4 million to 3 million men, cut the army's share of the state budget from 17.5 percent to less than 10 percent, and turned military industry factories to consumer production. In addition, the army has all but been shut out of politics. Finally, a program to acquire advanced weapons systems has been slowed because of budget constraints. `` If the army is not getting weapons, the least the government can give them is ranks,'' said one analyst. Analysts said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> had to award medals and ranks to its veterans, some of whom maintain a strong influence over the military, because it would have been an insult to award ranks only to those currently in service. `` Part of the reason all this took so long is that the veterans were bickering about who was to get which medal or which rank,'' one analyst said, citing Chinese sources. `` They are evidently very concerned with status.'' On Saturday, four classes of medals were awarded to about 80,000 veterans. According to the official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, military officers in the army will be divided into three grades with 11 ranks: four ranks of generals, four ranks of field officer _ senior colonel, colonel, lieutenant colonel and major, and three ranks of company officer: captain, lieutenant and second lieutenant. Previously, officers were given commands of groups such as platoons and divisions or were assigned to regional command posts, but there was no clear ranking hierarchy.
