<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of holiday travelers rushing to board a ferry caused a pier to collapse, leaving at least 31 people dead and injuring nearly 1,000, officials and news reports said today. Survivors said the upper level of a two-tiered pier in <LOCATION> Butterworth </LOCATION>, 180 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Kuala </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lumpur </LOCATION>, fell without warning Sunday afternoon. The upper section full of waiting passengers crashed onto people in cars and motorcycles on the lower level waiting to board the ferry. Victims were pinned beneath steel and timber while firefighters and port workers tried to free them and search for others. Emergency officials said all of those killed were believed to be <LOCATION> Malaysian </LOCATION>. About 300 people were on the pier and 3,000 were lined up behind them when the rush to the ferry began, port commission Chairman <PERSON> Syed </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohhamad </PERSON> <PERSON> Aidid </PERSON> told the national news agency <ORGANIZATION> Bernama </ORGANIZATION>. He said the 40-foot section that collapsed normally held about 200 people. The travelers were waiting to make the three-mile trip to <LOCATION> Penang </LOCATION> island for the Kwan Yin -LRB- Goddess of Mercy -RRB- Chinese religious celebration, held once every 60 years. `` Everything happened so fast, I could only scream for help,'' <PERSON> Gee </PERSON> <PERSON> Swee </PERSON> <PERSON> Cain </PERSON>, 41, a supervisor of the passenger ferry at the pier, told <ORGANIZATION> Bernama </ORGANIZATION>. As soon as the crowd rushed forward, the pier's wooden upper level gave way, sending hundreds of people plummeting to the lower level, said Mrs. Gee, who suffered chest and face injuries and a broken leg. Her husband and 5-year-old child were uninjured. `` I screamed for help and heard someone from above telling me to be patient because at that time nothing could be done to help me,'' Mrs. Gee told <ORGANIZATION> Bernama </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Cheong </PERS