<HEAD>Man Goes Home After Getting Lost During 600-Mile Journey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUNCIE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 74-year-old man who got lost on his way to the dentist and ended up 600 miles away says part of the problem was he'd never been away from home. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Collier </PERSON> returned to <LOCATION> Centreville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, on Sunday following a 17-hour journey that began at 5 a.m. Friday when he left for his appointment north of <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION>. Police stopped him at 10:15 p.m. Friday as he was driving west in the eastbound lane near <LOCATION> Muncie </LOCATION>, in central <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>. `` They knew I did n't have no business on that street and so they stopped me,'' he told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indianapolis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> on Sunday from the home he shares with his mother-in-law. `` I was glad the law stopped me. I was so glad, I did n't know what to do. I had n't eaten, I had n't drank any water. Authorities gave <PERSON> Collier </PERSON> food and a place to stay until members of his church arrived Sunday to take him home. `` It has been one of the strangest things I've ever been involved with,'' said <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, police Officer <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON>. `` I've been a policeman for 10 years and never had anything like this. It's a miracle he ever made it up here.'' <PERSON> Collier </PERSON> told police he was on his way to the dentist but could n't find the office. He said he turned around to head home. Instead, police believe, he wound up on Interstate 65, which runs from <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> to Mobile, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>. From <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION>, I-65 continues northwest toward <LOCATION> Lafayette </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Muncie </LOCATION> does not lie along the interstate. <PERSON> Collier </PERSON> said he stopped to buy gasoline in <LO