ther injuries.'' `` It has been shattered,'' <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> said of the building. The predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION>, which is fighting to end British rule in mainly <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, frequently attacks British military personnel. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> was `` deeply distressed to hear of the explosion'' when she arrived in <LOCATION> Perth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, on an official visit, her <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> office said. `` She is anxiously waiting for news of the people concerned and she sends deep sympathy for all the relatives concerned.'' In an interiew last week, <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON> <PERSON> Donnelly </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION>'s legal political wing <ORGANIZATION> Sinn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fein </ORGANIZATION>, said the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> recognized that killing British soldiers made more impact in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> than killing policemen or soldiers from <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>. `` So from that perspective, the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> certainly would like to target more British soldiers,'' he said. In May, after a 14-month lull, the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> resumed attacks on British army bases on the <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> continent. In the most recent attack, nine soldiers were injured on July 13 at <LOCATION> Duisburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Among the most serious <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> attacks on the army in mainland <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> were the July 20, 1982 double bombings in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Hyde </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> and Regent's Park killing 11 soldiers