<HEAD>Official Says Joint Efforts to Account for MIAs Could Start Within
3 Months</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Joint U.S.-Vietnam efforts to account for 1,761 Americans still listed as missing from the Vietnam War could begin soon, a <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official said today. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Lambertson </PERSON>, assistant secretary of state for East Asian and <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> Affairs, made that assessment following four days of meetings in <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> last week between Vietnamese officials and technical experts from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` While there are certain arrangments that will need to be worked out, we anticipate that joint activities, surveys, investigations and excavations could begin quite soon,'' <PERSON> Lambertson </PERSON> said on <ORGANIZATION> ABC-TV </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Good Morning America'' program. `` We anticipate a substantially higher level of activity over the next three months,'' said <PERSON> Lambertson </PERSON>, who termed the talks `` quite productive.'' He said the sites that will be examined remain to be determined. In the talks last week, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> agreed to consider <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s humanitarian problems in exchange for Vietnamese cooperation on the MIA matter. A leader of the effort to resolve the cases of those still listed as missing in action said on the same program that her group views last week's meeting as a sign the Vietnamese hope to put the issue to rest. `` We hope the Vietnamese are serious,'' said <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Mills </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffiths </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prisoners </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> War </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Missing </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </L