y, said other Soviet missiles banned by the superpower treaty would be destroyed over the next three years. The superpowers signed a treaty in December banning their medium - and shorter-range nuclear missiles It is the first arms agreement between the two nations that calls for the destruction of an entire class of weaponry. Under the treaty, the Soviets must eliminate 1,752 missiles with a range of between 310 miles and 3,410 miles that have been deployed or are in storage, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has said it will scrap 859 <ORGANIZATION> Pershing </ORGANIZATION> 2 and cruise missiles now stationed in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty, signed by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> general secretary <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, calls for each country to allow inspectors from the other side to verify that the rockets have been eliminated. On April 11, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> said it blew up six SS-12 missiles in a test designed to develop a method to destroy missiles under the treaty. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> also conducted such tests. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>, when asked by reporters how he evaluated the destruction of the missiles, said, `` I think it's a great event. I ` m very pleased to see it.'' His host, Soviet Defense Minister <PERSON> Dmitri </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON>, added, `` It means that we are starting to carry out the obligations which were achieved earlier, especially as a result of the four summit meetings in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Reykjavik </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>.'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said the destruction of the missiles `` will lead to a substantial lowering of the level of military confrontation in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and to the lessening of the risk of global nuclear conflict.''
