<FIRST>u i PM-UN-ChemicalWeapons 2ndLd-Writethru a0572 08-01 0657</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Chemical Weapons, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0572,0669</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Team Reports Iraq Using Mustard And Nerve Gas</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to update with Iranian comment. Picks up
4th graf pvs ``The U.N. inquiry ...'' </NOTE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> is continuing to use mustard and nerve gas `` on an intensive scale'' in its eight-year war with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> despite frequent pleas that it cease, according to a report by a team of <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> experts released today. `` The secretary-general can not but express his deep regret at the mission's conclusion that chemical weapons continue to be used against Iranian forces and positions,'' <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said in a statement. There was no immediate reaction from <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and the Iraqi Mission said officials were not available. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Tariq </PERSON> <PERSON> Aziz </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> for <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> talks on ending the Iran-Iraq war, last month acknowledged that <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> soldiers used chemical weapons. Ambassador <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Ja'afar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahallati </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> said today that the report `` only refers to allegations against <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, only cites nine soldiers.'' He added he hoped the report `` will only further motivate the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> to exert all pressure and leverage against <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> to accept a cease-fire and comprehensive settlement.'' The secretary-general is conducting talks with both sides on ending their war and implementing a cease-fire. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> inquiry was requested by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, which charged that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> had used the weapons frequently and on a massive scale, killing thousands of people in the spring. At <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s request, the team later went to <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>. The team said it examined <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> soldiers who had been injured by mustard gas, but did not conclude that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> used chemical weapons. Earlier <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> reports also have documented use of the weapons by <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> government has admitted using chemical weapons. Iranian officials had denied using the weapons. `` The danger of continuing escalation involving the use of those weapons of mass destruction, in violation of the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> Protocol and in spite of repeated findings ... and numerous appeals, is a frightening possibility which must be fully faced by all concerned and the international community as a whole,'' the secretary-general's statement said. In May the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> condemned the increasing use of chemical weapons in the Iran-Iraq war and urged restraint by both sides. `` We deeply regret to say that ... in spite of repeated appeals by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, chemical weapons continue to be used on an intensive scale against Iranian forces,'' the report by chemical warfare specialists said. The 53-page report consists of two parts based on visits to both <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> at the requests of the two government. It said clinical examinations of nine <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> soldiers showed their injuries had been produced by mustard gas. The Iraqis displayed mortar grenades that showed evidence of mustard gas and said they had been used by the Iranians, the team said. The section on <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s use of the weapons is more detailed, involving more patients and locations and studies of chemical bomb fragments. The report describes numerous injuries caused by mustard gas, but said the investigators could not confirm reports of nerve gas use because it disappears quickly. The medical chief and others in an Iranian war zone told the investigators that because it dissipates quickly and allows attackers to advance, the nerve gas was used against front line troops. They said mustard gas was used against rear areas to disrupt possible counterattacks because of its lasting effects. The team visited <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> from July 1 to 5, went to hospitals in <LOCATION> Bakhtaran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ahvas </LOCATION> and traveled to the war zone in the southwest. It visited <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> on July 10 and 11 and visited hospitals in As <LOCATION> Sulaymaniyah </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>. The team consisted of two chemical weapons specialists, Dr. <PERSON> Erik </PERSON> <PERSON> Dahlgren </PERSON> of the Swedish <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Umea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, and Dr. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Dominguez </PERSON> <PERSON> Carmona </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Universidad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Complutense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Madrid </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. They were accompanied by a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretariat official.
