<SECOND>AM-Pier Collapse,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witness Says Upper Pier Collapsed onto Auto Ramp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARI S. MANIAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUTTERWORTH, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A witness said Monday hundreds of people were standing on a section of ferry pier when it collapsed onto a ramp packed with cars and motorcycles, killing at least 31 people and injuring more than 800. <PERSON> Cheong </PERSON> <PERSON> Ah </PERSON> <PERSON> Chye </PERSON>, 21, was one of thousands waiting to board the ferry Sunday evening to attend a Chinese religious festival on <LOCATION> Penang </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, about three miles away, and said he was only about a yard from the section that collapsed. The ferry has an upper deck for passengers and a lower level for cars, trucks and motorcycles. <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Naga </PERSON> <PERSON> Rajan </PERSON>, a journalist for the daily <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Penang </ORGANIZATION>, said he had stepped onto the ferry only seconds before the disaster. He said hundreds of people had jammed the boarding area of the pier, justling and clambering over barriers. <PERSON> Rajan </PERSON> said: `` I had just stepped onto the ferry when I heard a loud noise. I turned around and saw that the portion from the beginning of the pathway to the ferry and the area around the sliding gate had fallen. `` I rushed down to the vehicle section of the ferry and saw that the whole platform around the area _ iron beams, planks and wires _ had collapsed with the people on it. It fell on vehicles on the lower floor going into the ferry. `` Then I saw people, bleeding in the head, face, arms and legs emerging from the debris. Many were covered with dirt and all were in shock. `` Some mothers, their faces bleeding, were looking for their children. Some people were crying, others offered prayers. A number of people were trapped under the iron beams and debris. Soon police and firemen arrived to pull them out.'' <PERSON> Mohamed </PERSON> <PERSON> Noorani </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamarun </PERSON>, deputy secretary of <LOCATION> Penang </LOCATION> state and head of the rescue operation, told reporters Monday that earlier reports of 35 dead were wrong. He said 31 people had been killed, including 13 who died in hospitals. He said only three of the casualties had been found to be foreigners: two from <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> and a French tourist with minor injuries. Prime Minister <PERSON> Mahathir </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohamad </PERSON> flew to <PERSON> Butterworth </PERSON> from <LOCATION> Kuala </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lumpur </LOCATION>, the capital city 180 miles to the southeast, and visited the injured at a government hospital. <PERSON> Mahathir </PERSON> said an immediate payment of about $ 800 would be made to the family of each of the dead and other compensation might be provided. Rescue officials said most of the debris had been cleared away and no more bodies or survivors were expected to be found. <PERSON> Butterworth </PERSON> has two ferry piers. The one remaining intact resumed operation Monday after a safety inspection. Only passengers were allowed on the pier. Vehicles were ordered to use the bridge that links this port of 50,000 people to <LOCATION> Penang </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> across the Strait of <LOCATION> Malacca </LOCATION>. The rescue center said all but two of the dead had been indentified and the total number injured was 863, including 417 still hospitalized.
