<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If, as <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> said, everyone will be famous for 15 minutes, they'll be able to time their moments in the sun with a Warhol-designed watch, record the event in a Warhol-decorated diary and wear clothes inspired by the late pop artist. A line of Warhol products ranging from business planning calendars to watches costing several thousand dollars should appear in retail stores early next year, said <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlaifer </PERSON>, president of Atlanta-based <ORGANIZATION> Schlaifer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which owns the marketing rights to <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> and his work. <PERSON> Schlaifer </PERSON>, whose company until earlier this year marketed Cabbage Patch Kids dolls, said the Warhol products are still being developed. But he said they would include clothing, bedding, jewelry and paper products, such as calendars, posters and diaries. `` We're targeting a young, thinking audience where the Warhol attitude and image is reflected,'' <PERSON> Schlaifer </PERSON> said. Some of the items will bear <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON>'s likeness or that of his work, while others will aim to capture the spirit of the artist, <PERSON> Schlaifer </PERSON> said. Moderately priced items will be sold in `` better department and specialty stores,'' <PERSON> Schlaifer </PERSON> said, while the expensive products will be availble only through more exclusive outlets. <PERSON> Schlaifer </PERSON>, who commissioned <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> to do a series of portraits of the Cabbage Patch Kids, said he proposed to the artist a massive marketing effort in 1985 and made a formal presentation a year later. The talks slowed down but were revived only a week before <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> died on Feb. 22, 1987, at the age of 58, <PERSON> Schlaifer </PERSON> said. The deal giving <PERSON> Schlaifer </PERSON> the marketing rights was finalized later with the <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> estate, he said. <PERSON> Schlaifer </PERSON> said <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON>, a former ad man who well known for his silver-wigged celebrity status as well as for his works of art, was enthusiastic about the idea. `` With his sense of commerce, and what we outlined in terms of exposure, he was very excited,'' <PERSON> Schlaifer </PERSON> said. `` <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> was unique in how he designed himself. In a way, he made himself as unique as his art.'' Despite <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON>'s flair for publicity and his unconventional approach to art, <PERSON> Schlaifer </PERSON> acknowledged there may be criticism of such blatant commercial use of the artist's work. But he defended his plans, saying <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> was not averse to commercialism and noting that even the most respected museums have gift shops. `` Virtually anything anyone does is subject to criticism,'' he said. `` The question is, is it appropriate? <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> had a strong commercial instinct. `` All museums have huge product enterprises that help support the museum and educate the public. I'm not sure where that criticism has validity, other than the position that art should only be in the museums or in books.'' <PERSON> Schlaifer </PERSON> said <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> did not limit himself to creating museum pieces. <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> also made movies, started `` Interview'' magazine and designed album covers for a number of rock and roll bands. `` He was commercial in a non-commercial way _ that was the inherent irony in everything <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> did,'' <PERSON> Schlaifer </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Schlaifer </PERSON> is banking on continuing fascination with <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> and his work. `` There's sort of an automatic excitement with anything connected with the <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> name,'' he said. He noted that an auction earlier this year of artwork and other items owned by <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> drew crowds and large sums of money, and said displays of <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> art, particularly a traveling exhibit planned next year by <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Museum of Modern Art, should heighten interest. `` If anything, the acceptance is higher now than when we originally proposed this,'' <PERSON> Schlaifer </PERSON> said. `` He's a major artist by any definition. He gets more press dead than most celebrities do alive.''
