<HEAD>Chronology of Postponements on Shuttle Flight</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Space Shuttle Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Following are key dates in the continued postponement of the space shuttle flight: Jan. 28, 1986 _ Space shuttle Challenger blows up shortly after launch, killing crew of seven. May 15, 1986 _ <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Aldrich </PERSON>, manager of the shuttle system, tells <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> committee that target date for next launch, of Discovery, is July 15, 1987. Oct. 3, 1986 _ <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> announces target date of Feb. 18, 1988 for Discovery launch. Jan. 14, 1987 _ <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> reports that <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> will not have time to evaluate or incorporate any safety changes if it attempts to meet Feb. 18, 1988 launch target. April 21, 1987 _ <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> announces it can not meet Feb. 18, 1988 date, and slates additional tests. No new target announced. June 2, 1987 _ Rear Adm. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Truly </PERSON> says that Discovery will be launched June 2, 1988 if all tests go according to schedule. Nov. 23, 1987 _ <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> recommends additional testing of solid-fuel engine, which might require postponing June launch. Dec. 29, 1987 _ <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> announces that June launch date has been postponed because of failure of booster rocket nozzle during a test. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> officials say launch date will be moved back 6-10 weeks. Jan. 11, 1988 _ <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> administrator <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> says launch will be between mid-July and mid-August of 1988. Jan. 27, 1988 _ <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> sets Aug. 4 as launch date. April 26, 1988 _ Shuttle manbager <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Aldrich </PERSON> says launch will be pushed back at least until Aug. 14 because of unexpected delays in assembling redesigned booster rockets. May 4, 1988 _ <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> says Aug. 25 is a possible launch date, although it might be early September. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> subsequently selects Aug. 31 date. June 10, 1988 _ The external fuel tank is joined to the solid rocket boosters, and astronaut <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Crippen </PERSON>, deputy director of shuttle operations, says `` we've got a shot'' at meeting the Aug. 31 target. Test firing of shuttle's liquid-fuel engines is set for July 18. July 15, 1988 _ Discovery sprang a small gas leak in one of its steering engines, and <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> said there was a possibility of additional delay in the launch, now set for Sept. 3. July 22, 1988 _ <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> announce two-day delay in test firing of main engines, which had been planned for July 30. July 29, 1988 _ <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> postpones test firing again, setting date of Aug. 4, after discovering leak in a hydrogen line during fueling. Aug. 1, 1988 _ Another hydrogen leak is detected, but <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> goes ahead with the countdown rehearsal; no decision on whether to postpone the test-firing will be made until Tuesday.
