<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of Poles marking the 44th anniversary of the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> uprising against the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> demanded Monday that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> end its silence over alleged atrocities against Poles during World War II. Speakers also called for less interference from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and demanded the right to hold free elections. `` <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> has to realize that we fought on all fronts of the war, but we still have not regained our freedom,'' said <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziembinski </PERSON>, an independent opposition activist. Crowds filled <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Powazki </LOCATION> military cemetery to pay homage to those who fell during the 63-day revolt against Nazi occupation. The Nazis crushed the uprising. More than 245,000 people were killed and 85 percent of the city was destroyed. While scores of Poles lighted candles and laid flowers on the graves of friends and family members, hundreds of others gathered around a granite monument to Polish officers murdered in the <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> forest near the Soviet city of <LOCATION> Smolensk </LOCATION>. The massacre remains one of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s most bitter wartime memories and a sore spot in its relations with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The Soviets have never acknowledged responsibility for the incident, in which 4,300 Polish military officers were shot to death and left in a mass grave. Western historical sources indicate the Poles were murdered on the orders of Soviet dictator <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> in the spring of 1940. But official Soviet and Polish histories claim that the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> killed them in 1941. A banner draped across the monument Monday read: `` Give us truth, <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> 1940.'' Later, a group of youths raised a ban