<HEAD>Ranks Restored In Chinese Army</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> on Monday brought back military ranks to its army in a move to modernize its fighting force and boost morale after years of personnel cuts and tight budgets. The move came on the 61st anniversary of the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> and 23 years after <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-tung </PERSON> banned ranks as inappropriate to his classless peasant army. On Oct. 1, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s national day, soldiers are to don new uniforms with insignia designating their military positions. The government also issued regulations spelling out awards to be given to servicemen and their families `` so as to encourage their dedicated spirit in defending and building the motherland.'' The new regulations guarantee servicemen that they will not lose their farmland when they are conscripted, as well offer pensions to those disabled in combat and pay damages to the families of those who died in combat. On Saturday, <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> Secretary General <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON> and other senior leaders gathered at the Great Hall of the People to bestow medals on more than 80,000 veterans. Western military analysts in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the ranking system was designed to raise the morale of the army, after troop strength and state funding were slashed in the past decade and many military factories were converted to civilian use. The analysts said a need for reinstating ranks became evident after the Chinese army's embarrassing showing in a brief 1979 border war with <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. `` These kinds of units need a strict command structure, with a clear delineation as to who is giving and who is receiving the orders,'' said a diplomat, who spoke on condition of anonymity. `` Before today they did n't have that.'' The analysts said Monday's move is also aimed at ridding the army of leftist influences. In 1965, <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> abolished military ranks as part of his attempt to create a radically egalitarian society, in which a massive peasant army would would be called on to fight a `` people's war.'' <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON>, who rose to power in 1978, has rejected <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>'s concept and has tried to create a professional army Today, 70 percent of military commanders have college educations, compared to 1.6 percent in 1982. <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>, who controls the military as head of the central military commission, has reduced the size of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s armed forces to 3 million, from 4 million in 1985, and has introduced modern technology. He has also shaved the military's share of the government budget from 17.5 percent in 1978 to less than 10 percent. <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> has also supported the transfer of `` cadres,'' or officers, to civilian duty as part of an effort to cut the oversized corps, many of whom were either aging or poorly trained. Among the 1 million soldiers demobilized in the past few years, 450,000 were cadres. The government announced that an additional 100,000 officers would be transferred to a civilian staff of educators and specialists.
</TEXT>
