<SECOND>AM-Sobriety Check Lanes,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Says Anti-Drunk Checklanes Unconstitutional</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Roadblocks to check drivers for signs of intoxication are ineffective and unconstitutional, the <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled Monday in upholding a lower court's ruling against the state. `` While the goals of the sobriety checkpoint program are laudable, the program fails to qualify as a reasonable seizure under the Fourth Amendment,'' the three-judge appeals panel wrote in a unanimous opinion. The state attorney general's office did not immediately have a comment about the ruling or any plans for further appeals. The <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1975 refused to rule on the constitutionality of systematic roadblock stops. Monday's ruling upholds the conclusions of <ORGANIZATION> Wayne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Stacey </PERSON>, who issued a permanent injunction stopping the roadblocks on the grounds that they violated both the federal and state constitutions. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> chapter, praised <PERSON> Stacey </PERSON>'s 60-page opinion as `` the most extensive, definitive, best-reasoned analysis in the country of the alleged effectiveness of sobriety roadblocks and the extent to which they intrude upon the civil liberties of innocent motorists.'' `` I'm glad it was upheld,'' he said. `` Now the state should do what we suggested all the time, namely get down to the business of cracking down on drunken driving without violating the rights of innocent motorists.'' The program devised by state police followed a blueprint drafted from check lane laws in 37 other states and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>. Its prime model was <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>'s program, and the opinion noted the testimony of a <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> lieutenant who said checkpoints there yielded few drunken driving arrests. Gov. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Blanchard </PERSON>, who pushed through the program and made it one of his top priorities in 1986, would not comment until his staff had time to review the decision, spokesman <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said. The issue of anti-drunk checkpoints has come up in courts in about half of the states with mixed results, according to the <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> appellate opinion. State courts in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> have upheld the roadblocks while they have been struck down in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has n't ruled on anti-drunk roadblocks but implied in a 1979 case that they are acceptable. The high court said police may not selectively stop drivers who are not suspected of breaking any law, but mentioned roadblocks among possible acceptable alternatives. In 1986, the high court refused to hear arguments in a case challenging <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>'s roadblocks. That decision had the effect of letting <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> continue the checkpoints.
