<FIRST>r i AM-Anglicans     08-01 0678</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Anglicans,0700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anglican Bishops Reject Call To Keep from Consecrating Women
Bishops</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANTERBURY, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The world's Anglican bishops on Monday rejected a call to refrain from consecrating women bishops and accepted a compromise resolution that such elevation of women should not divide the <ORGANIZATION> Anglican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communion </ORGANIZATION>. On a show of hands, the bishops voted 423-28 with 19 abstentions to maintain links with any of their 27 self-governing churches which consecrate a woman bishop, even if they disagree. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Episcopalians and the Canadian and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> Anglicans say they may consecrate a woman bishop by the end of this year. The resolution preserving the unity of the 70 million-member Anglican Communion was drafted by conference participants who considered it for most of the first two weeks of the three-week <ORGANIZATION> Lambeth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>. It is the bishops' first gathering in 10 years. On a secret ballot, the bishops voted 277-187 against a resolution proposed by Archbishop of <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION> <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> that the churches should `` refrain from consecrating a woman as bishop'' to avoid further damage over the issue of women priests and bishops. Archbishop of Canterbury <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON>, spiritual leader of the Church of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Anglican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communion </ORGANIZATION>, said after the two votes that despite differences of opinion, the conference acted in a spirit of unity. <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON> said before the vote that however the count went, he agreed with its recommendation that he appoint a commission to prepare guidelines for relations among the churches once women bishops are appointed. He said his commission would `` start meetings well before the end of this year.'' <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON> said of the compromise resolution, `` It was n't a fudge _ it was very carefully worked out respecting of differences and the determination to live together. ... Tell me what other way you hold a communion together when it is deeply divided about something which is of great importance to some people and of little importance to others in the mission of the church.'' <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, metropolitan of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wales </LOCATION>, said his resolution simply invited the conference to express its mind. `` It is contrary to the explicit teaching of the New Testament that women be given responsibility for the authority of the Scriptures in the congregation,'' he said. But Presiding Bishop <PERSON> Edmond </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, which has ordained hundreds of women priests in the past 11 years, differed. `` Restraint is not a true option,'' <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> said. `` When we heard or read that it is only a matter of time before women will be elected bishops in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, this is not a statement of defiance. It is simply looking into our future as a province -LRB- church -RRB- based on our past and our present. `` Ordained women are already a feature of our church life. Our people have been blessed by the priestly ministry of ordained women for more than a decade. Therefore, the people of our diocese move ahead toward calling women to be bishops in a way that is authentic to our experience.'' Many of the Anglican bishops, clergy and laity oppose ordaining women. About 1,200 women priests have been ordained by a minority of the churches, mostly by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Episcopalians. Opponents call the practice contrary to Scripture and tradition. They say they could not accept a woman bishop though they might eventually accept women priests. Bishops are regarded as the successors of the Apostles of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON>. All were men. Bishop <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Pwaisiho </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Malaita </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> territory of <LOCATION> Melanesia </LOCATION>, denounced ordaining women as `` Satanic.'' `` I think you are not listening to us _ and my color does n't help, either,'' said <PERSON> Pwaisiho </PERSON>, who is black `` No woman should be consecrated for the sake of the unity we seek,'' appealed another African prelate, Bishop <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Nwankiti </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Owerri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>. But a black prelate from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, Bishop <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, said white men who had long prevented blacks from becoming bishops were now using the same arguments against women. `` In Christ there is neither male nor female,'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said.
