<HEAD>Biaggi's 1987 Brooklyn Conviction Upheld; Jury Still Out in
Wedtech</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal appeals court Monday upheld the 1987 conviction of Rep. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, while a jury deliberated racketeering charges against him in the <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> corruption trial. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Constance </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> Motley </PERSON> immediately sequestered the jury in the <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> case at the request of <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>'s lawyer, who called the appeals court ruling `` a great problem for us. <PERSON> Motley </PERSON> had planned to sequester the jury beginning Tuesday night after late arriving jurors on Monday were confronted by demonstrators outside the courthouse, chanting `` Down with political corruption'' and `` Compensate <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> workers.'' The jury ended its third day of deliberations Monday without a verdict. Monday's ruling by the 2nd <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> upheld <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>'s Sept. 22, 1987, conviction for obstructing justice and accepting an unlawful gratuity. <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> was convicted of accepting free <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> vacations with a female companion from former <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> Democratic leader <PERSON> Meade </PERSON> <PERSON> Esposito </PERSON>. The appeals panel also upheld the conviction of the 80-year-old <PERSON> Esposito </PERSON>. <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>, 71, a 10-term congressman from the <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION>, was convicted by a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> jury in <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> on three felony counts: accepting an illegal gratuity, traveling across state lines to accept the gratuity and obstruct