<HEAD>Doctor Quits In Animal-To-Human Transplants Controversy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A British surgeon involved in a plan to use pigs' organs for human transplants abruptly quit the project Monday in a dispute with colleagues, but said research would continue Dr. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Bewick </PERSON> said fellow researchers at <LOCATION> Dulwich </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, in south <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, told him to `` shut up or get out'' following a day where battle lines were drawn between scientists and animal rights activists. <PERSON> Bewick </PERSON>, 52, a kidney transplant specialist, said the research team was furious that without their consent he had announced the hospital intended to study the feasibility of transplanting kidneys, livers and hearts from pigs into people. Animal rights groups responded to the press coverage by labeling the idea a `` horror fantasy'' and `` gross abuse of animal life.'' They asked the government to ban the project. <PERSON> Bewick </PERSON> said the research team feared the controversy might harm its chances of obtaining facilities to carry out the work. `` For the sake of the group and the work they are doing, I decided it would be right for me to leave,'' <PERSON> Bewick </PERSON> said. He stressed the group had `` the brains and technical skills'' to proceed without him. A hospital spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said he would meet with <PERSON> Bewick </PERSON> and the research team Tuesday to assess the situation. <PERSON> Bewick </PERSON> was quoted in the Independent newspaper Monday, as saying in earlier comments that the program posed `` no ethical problem... Animal kidneys could save the lives of thousands of people who die because we do not have an off-the-shelf kidney.'' Before withdrawing from the project, <PERSON> Bewick </PERSON> had offered to meet with animal rights groups to discuss their concerns. He said he feared attacks on his personal property and the hospital. Attempts to transplant animal organs into humans, including sheep, baboon and chimpanzee hearts, have failed. In what was probably the most publicized case, Dr. <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> transplanted a baboon heart into a 12-day-old infant, dubbed Baby Fae, at the <LOCATION> Loma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Linda </LOCATION> medical facility in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> in 1984. She died 20 days later. A year after the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> baby's death, <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> said she died not from rejection of heart tissue but from another form of rejection which he said he believes is possible to avoid. <PERSON> Bewick </PERSON> said over the weekend that the hospital research team found a way to filter out antibodies that cause humans to reject donor organs. He said the new technique had helped 20 patients accept human kidneys more easily. Researchers had planned experiments this fall to see whether the technique worked between different species of animals _ pigs and sheep. If successful, <PERSON> Bewick </PERSON> had estimated pig-to-human transplants could begin within three years. But the British Union for the Abolition of Vivisection condemned the research program as a `` gross abuse of animal life and waste of health care resources.'' `` The experimental animals will undoubtedly suffer greatly both physically and mentally despite the fact that anesthetics will be used,'' an unidentified spokesman said. <PERSON> Bewick </PERSON> had said pigs were the most suitable animals because their organs physiologically most resemble those of humans. Another pressure group, Animal Concern <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, said animal research would be unnecessary if more people agreed to donate their organs after death. `` The idea of breeding pigs as living organ banks owes more to sick horror fantasy than medical science'' said a spokesman, who refused to be identified. `` I hope the -LRB- government -RRB- will use some common sense and ban this approach.'' The Sunday Times quoted <PERSON> Bewick </PERSON> as saying he had obtained approval for the experiments from the hospital's ethics committee. A spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, speaking on condition of anonymity, said that panel's approval made the project acceptable if it seemed likely to yield some benefit. She said society ultimately would decide the future of animal-to-human transplants. The controversy highlighted the need for a national ethics committee, she said.
