<HEAD>With AM-Dukakis Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A preliminary <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> inquiry into allegations the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> administration gave developers confidential information about prison-siting plans has ended with no charges filed. Law enforcement sources, speaking only on condition they not be named, said the investigation turned up no evidence of federal violations. <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Cloherty </PERSON> said, `` The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> is conducting no further investigation with regard to the placing of a state prison at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Braintree </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, and-or the procurement of land for that prison.'' He declined to characterize the outcome of the inquiry other than to say no charges had been filed. <PERSON> Cloherty </PERSON> also declined to say whether any evidence had been forwarded for grand jury review. However, two law enforcement sources said the inquiry found no evidence that federal laws had been broken. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON>, deputy press spokesman for the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor, refused to say whether law enforcement officials had informed the administration that the inquiry had ended. But when told of the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> statement and law enforcement comment, <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> said: `` It was always our contention that this was an open process, above the board. We will go forward with the implementation of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Braintree </LOCATION> plan.'' Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in 1986 formally announced plans to build a 500-bed, medium-security prison in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Braintree </LOCATION> at the site of a defunct religious academy. The site had been discussed informally for a prison or other state institution beginning in 1984. Prison opponents, largely residents of the rural town of 800 people, complained that the inmate and staff population would overrun their farming community. Later, some opponents alleged that the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> administration, unable to buy the land directly because the church that owned it had agreed with town officials not to sell it for projects including a prison, leaked its interest in the site to two developers who bought it and then offered it to the state. The allegations have been cited by <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> critics to attack the good-government pledges that are a major theme of his presidential campaign. National publicity followed the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>'s confirmation June 23 that a preliminary inquiry was under way. At that time, the agency said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> himself was not a target of any investigation. The developers, <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Striar </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON>, offered the land to the state for $ 9.5 million. But the state has offered only $ 5 million, citing three appraisals, commissioned by the state, that listed its value at or just below $ 5 million. <PERSON> Striar </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON> have rejected the state's offer as too low but the state notified <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Braintree </LOCATION> officials in a letter mailed last week that the purchase would go forward. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradshaw </PERSON>, associate deputy commissioner of the state Division of Capital Planning and Operations, said the state will take the land by eminent domain if the owners do not change their stance. The seizure likely will take place in mid-October or November, he said Monday. <PERSON> Bradshaw </PERSON> said his agency had not been informed that the inquiry had ended. `` None of my people were questioned as part of it and we have n't talked to them today either,'' he said `` We did n't feel it was necessary for any investigation. However, the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> has a role to complete and if they have done that and feel there is no evidence of wrongdoing then I'm certainly happy.''
