<HEAD>Government Ordered To Change Or Delete Unconstitutionally Vague
Language</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge has ordered the government to change or delete unconstitutionally vague language in pledges signed by 1.7 million government workers not to disclose top-secret information. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> Gasch </PERSON> ordered the modification in the non-disclosure pledges signed by government workers with access to top-secret information must sign to retain their security clearances. In an order signed Friday and made public Monday, the judge said the government must provide a more specific definition of the term `` classifiable information.'' In signing the various pledges, government employees promise not to make unauthorized disclosures of top-secret information or `` classifiable information.'' <PERSON> Gasch </PERSON> gave the <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oversight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> 60 days to notify the federal employees of the government's definition or `` classifiable information'' or to declare the term inoperative. Until that notification is made, the government can not penalize employees who disclose `` classifiable information,'' the judge said. A more specific definition must also be included in forms presented to federal employees who have not yet signed the pledge or the term must be deleted, the judge said. The ruling was made in a lawsuit by two federal employees unions that contended the pledges use throughout the executive branch empowered government agencies to penalize whistleblowers by classifying information after it was disclosed to the press or members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Gasch </PERSON> suggested that the security agency, headed by <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Garfinkel </PERSON>, could adopt a definition published late last year in the Federal Register. That regulation defined `` classifiable information'' as any unstamped material or oral conversations that an employee has a good reason to know should be classified. Such information would include material that was in the process of being reviewed for classification, according to the regulatory definition published Dec. 21, 1987. <PERSON> Gasch </PERSON> upheld the validity of that definition, saying: `` much classified information is not marked as such because it has not been examined by a classification authority. The govenrment nevertheless has a substantial interest in safeguarding that information.'' The 1987 definition `` simply requires that employees consider whether they have reason to believe that unmarked information is classified or should be classified and is in the process of becoming so,'' <PERSON> Gasch </PERSON> said. The regulation was offered to allay concerns raised by the plaintiffs who brought the lawsuit. But <PERSON> Gasch </PERSON> said that `` until an employee becomes aware of the regulatory definition, he can not know what ` classifiable' information does not include, for example, information that only speculation suggests will become classified. `` Notice of the definition is essential,'' the judge said. The decision was hailed by both sides of the dispute. <PERSON> Garfinkel </PERSON> noted that <PERSON> Gasch </PERSON> had upheld the general principle that federal employees can be required to sign secrecy pledges. `` I think essentially its a victory for the broader principle. It will require us to do something more as far as the forms that hae already been signed is concerned,'' <PERSON> Garfinkel </PERSON> said. `` We will have to decide which option to take.'' <PERSON> Patti </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldman </PERSON>, an attorney for <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Litigation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a consumer lobby that filed a friend-of-the-court brief for several members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, said the order `` teaches a lesson to the government that they have to be more careful when they are crafting these agreements.''
