<BYLINE>Soviets Say Southern Africa Settlement Possible in `Future'
^By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Soviet official said Monday there is a good chance four-way talks that resume Tuesday will produce a peace settlement soon in southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Anatoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Adamyshin </PERSON>, Soviet deputy foreign minister, made the comments after two days of consultations with <PERSON> Chester </PERSON> <PERSON> Crocker </PERSON>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assistant secretary of state for <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> affairs. <PERSON> Crocker </PERSON> is mediating the talks among <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, which began three months ago and resume Tuesday. Agreement on guidelines for a settlement was reached during last month's round in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` We think there are chances of success in these negotiations,'' <PERSON> Adamyshin </PERSON> told a news conference. `` It appears that all sides are serious about seeking a settlement. ... It is possible that there will be a settlement in the nearest future.'' Asked to be more specific, he said a target date of Sept. 29 had been mentioned. That is the 10th anniversary of <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Security Council Resolution 435 on independence for <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, also known as <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, which <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has controlled since World War I. All negotiators accepted the resolution as a basis of the `` Principles for a Peaceful Settlement in <LOCATION> Southwestern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'' agreed upon July 20. The list of 14 principles, the first document to which the three countries have agreed, link independence for <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> to withdrawal of the estimated 50,000 Cuban troops in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. Cuban soldiers have helped the Marxist government against rebels of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> for the Total Independence of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION>, who have fought since <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> became independent of <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> in 1975. The movement, led by <PERSON> Jonas </PERSON> <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON>, is supported by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The agreement on principles emerged from three rounds of talks held since May in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Military commanders of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> met in <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Verde </LOCATION> and were said to have made progress on disengaging <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> and South African soldiers who face each other along the <LOCATION> Angola-Namibia </LOCATION> frontier. <PERSON> Crocker </PERSON> has called the list of principles `` an important step'' but says hard bargaining remains. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has assigned a special observer, although it is not a participant in the negotiations. <PERSON> Adamyshin </PERSON> was asked about a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official's statement that the superpowers find increasing common ground on southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, and acknowledged there is `` more understanding.'' He added, however, that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military aid to <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> `` is unlawful and must be stopped. On that point, we differ with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' Later in the news conference, he said the aid issue must be settled between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOC