to move up graf saying EPA expects shortage of CFC compounds will
enable producers to raise prices with no increase in production
costs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said Monday it wants the government to capture expected windfall corporate profits that could reach $ 7 billion during future cuts in production of chemicals that destroy the Earth's protective ozone layer. But the agency said it had not decided how to do that, and one major producer said it doubts that there will be major windfalls as the chemicals _ chlorofluorocarbon or <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> compounds _ are cut back. Under <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s expectations, the shortage of <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> compounds will enable producers to raise prices with no increase in production costs. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> disclosed that it was considering regulations that could require manufacturers to pay fees to the government equal to their extra profits; could require recycling or other controls on manufacturing processes; or could require companies to buy manufacturing rights from the government at auctions open to anyone. The agency announced final adoption of detailed regulations, including production quotas, to carry out last year's treaty obliging major nations to cut <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> production 50 percent by 1998. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> expects enough countries to ratify the treaty for it to take effect next Jan. 1. Eleven nations accounting for two-thirds of world production must ratify; six including the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> have done so. <PERSON> Eileen </PERSON> <PERSON> Claussen </PERSON>, acting deputy <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> administrator for air programs, said the agency leans toward fees, perhaps supplemented by direct controls, as a way of capturing windfall profits. The president's <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION>, on the other hand, favors auctioning the production rights. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s authority to proceed without legislation is cloudy, Ms. <PERSON> Claussen </PERSON> said. An auction, she said, could be administratively unworkable if 10,000 small companies participate. `` If it was judged to be illegal, we would have nothing. We would n't be in compliance with the <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> protocol,'' she said. And she said, `` There's a lot of concern about hoarding,'' in which large companies like auto manufacturers would keep smaller concerns, such as those making plastic foams for furniture cushions, from getting production rights. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> wants to the government to get the increased profits because `` our concern is the incentive producers might have for keeping an existing product in production,'' delaying the switch to environmentally harmless alternatives, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>, project officer for the regulations. The largest producer of CFCs, <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said it believed no action was needed to take extra profits away from the producers because they would be small or nonexistent. `` One producer after another is announcing progress with substitutes,'' said <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Steed </PERSON>, environmental manager for CFCs for <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION>. Substitution `` is the driving force we're going to see ... if we can fund development at the rate we think we need, we'll be doing well.'' <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said the increase in profits over the 1986 level could range from $ 1.8 billion if user companies rapidly find alternatives to $ 7.2 billion if <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> compounds are kept on the market as long as possible. The <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> treaty binds participating countries to a reduction of 20 percent in <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> production in 1993 and a further 30 percent cut in 1998, all calculated from a 1986 base. The long-lived <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> compounds ascend to the ozone layer 15 to 25 miles high, where since about 1960 they have destroyed about 2.5 percent of the ozone protecting humans from skin cancer from the sun's ultra-violet rays normally blocked by ozone. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> estimates that every percent decrease in ozone results on 43,000 additional skin cancer cases in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Currently there are about 500,000 cases a year. The regulation will prevent about 3.7 million early deaths among people now alive in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> or to be born by the year 2075, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> estimated. Financially, `` The impact on the consumer will be very small,'' because <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> use is such a small part of the cost of production, and large price increases will be easily absorbed even if the increase is five - or six-fold, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> said CFCs are widely used as refrigeration fluids, solvents and plastic foam blowing agents. They are banned as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aerosol propellants but still used as propellants abroad. A new car typically contains 2.5 pounds of a CFC compound used as air conditioning fluid, costing about $ 1.50. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s regulations, if triggered by the treaty going into effect, mean that in the 12 months beginning July 1, 1989, the five <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturers will be bound by these manufacturing quotas, to the nearest million pounds: <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, 336 million pounds; <ORGANIZATION> Allied-Signal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 171 million; <ORGANIZATION> Pennwalt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 86 million; <ORGANIZATION> Kaiser </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemicals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, 62 million and <ORGANIZATION> Racon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, 30 million. Similar quotas apply separately to the sum of production plus imports minus exports: <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION>, 308 million pounds, <ORGANIZATION> Allied-Signal </ORGANIZATION>, 163 million; <ORGANIZATION> Pennwalt </ORGANIZATION>, 84 million; <PERSON> Kaiser </PERSON>, 61 million; <ORGANIZATION> Racon </ORGANIZATION>, 30 million and 10 companies whose imports totaled almost 13 million pounds. Related compounds called halons used in fire extinguishers will be subject to similar quotas starting in 1992. The companies may transfer these quotas among themselves.
