<HEAD>Paralyzed Man Dangles in Wheelchair on Brooklyn Bridge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A paraplegic in a wheelchair, carrying fireworks and samurai swords, lowered himself on a rope Monday from the <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION> and dangled 75 feet above the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> for more than an hour. <PERSON> Ramond </PERSON> <PERSON> Masa </PERSON>, 40, of the <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION>, who called himself `` <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s No 1 Stuntman,'' claimed he had dangled from the 105-year-old landmark for seven hours. His stunt forced traffic on the bridge to be halted as the morning rush hour began. About 30 officers from the police harbor unit, emergency service officers and ambulance personnel rushed to the bridge, which connects lower <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>, after a tugboat operator spotted <PERSON> Masa </PERSON>. He was eventually persuaded to lower himself to the river, where he was guided onto a police launch. <PERSON> Masa </PERSON> said he did it because `` I wanted to inspire these guys -LRB- in wheelchairs -RRB- to get up from the hospital, and do something for their communities and their families.'' He refused medical attention at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Infirmary-Beekman </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Downtown </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> and was taken to a police station, where he was booked on charges of disorderly conduct, unlawful carrying of a knife, and unlawful dealing with fireworks, according to police spokesman Sgt. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON>. <PERSON> Masa </PERSON>, a large man with huge biceps and broad shoulders who also uses the name <PERSON> El-Shah </PERSON> <PERSON> Muhammed </PERSON> <PERSON> El-Ratuli </PERSON>, was given a summons for a Sept. 19 court date and released. The man, whose legs are paralyzed, initially told reporters his name was `` Megaman.'' He handed out red, white and blue business cards that proclaimed, `` Living on the edge is my business _ American No. 1 Stuntmen.'' <PERSON> Masa </PERSON> said he lost the use of his legs when he was shot by a sniper in 1977. He said his dangle off the <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION> was his first experience as a stuntman. `` I planned for three months to do something real crazy to get into the Guinness record book,'' he said. After a short vacation, <PERSON> Masa </PERSON> said he plans to `` hang on the Statue of Liberty or the World Trade Center. Maybe I'll take a shot at the Eiffel Tower in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Masa </PERSON> said he was dropped off in the center of the span at about midnight by his brother, whom he refused to identify. Dragging his wheelchair and two nylon bags containing the swords and firecrackers behind him, <PERSON> Masa </PERSON> crawled to the edge of the span, where he tied a nylon cord around his waist, through the wheelchair and secured it to a five-inch thick piece of bridgework. Then, he pushed the wheelchair off the bridge and shimmied down the rope after it. He was noticed by a passing tugboat, which notified police about dawn. `` He had looped it in some way that he could go down the rope sitting in a wheelchair,'' said police Capt. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Plackenmeyer </PERSON>. <PERSON> Masa </PERSON> said he had planned to don a Ninja costume, light the six super M-80's _ the equivalent of about 1 -LCB- sticks of dynamite _ and hold the two samurai swords, each about three feet long, before he jumped into the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. He abandoned that plan after the two nylon bags containing his gear fell into the river during the rescue effort. <PERSON> Masa </PERSON> expressed no remorse over the traffic jam. `` This is <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. They -LRB- the commuters -RRB- like the excitement on Monday morning.''
