<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION> Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and four Central American foreign ministers issued a joint declaration Monday calling for peace and democracy in the region but without mentioning <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, however, used a closing news conference to take several verbal swipes at <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s leftist Sandinista government and to put in a plug for congressional approval of additional aid to the Nicaraguan rebels, known as Contras. <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> was not invited to the meeting. The joint communique, issued at the end of a three-hour meeting, was a watered-down version of an earlier declaration drafted shortly after <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>'s last visit to <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> in late June. <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> said Sunday that <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> had demanded changes in the proposed communique. The initial draft was said to be 10 pages long and to contain a harsh criticism of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> for its failure to live up to a Central American peace agreement signed by it and its four neighbors a year ago. But as issued, the declaration contained only 10 paragraphs, reafirming the respect of the five countries `` for peace, democracy, security, social justice and economic development'' in all of <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. While obviously aimed at <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, it did not mention the country by name. The final version also said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the four Central American nations agreed on the need to establish `` authentic democratic governments in the entire region as indispensable for peace.'' It said the five countries `` reafirmed that authentic democracy requires, among other requisites, political pluralism, freedom of association, freedom of the press, an impartial justice system that guarantees due process, an apolitical armed forces, an honest and open electoral system and respect for human and individual rights.'' At a news conference closing their meeting, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said the Contras `` are an important element, expressing a strong desire for freedom and democracy in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and we continue to support them. `` I did n't come here basically to discuss that subject, and we did n't have very much discussion of it, although I certainly hope that we will extend funding for the Contras,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said. `` I think it is very important.'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said his discussions with the foreign ministers centered on economic development `` and how we might organize ourselves to pursue that more systematically.'' Upon arriving in <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> shared common goals of democracy, the rule of law and economic progress. But he acknowledged problems in reaching those objectives. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> spoke with reporters before meeting with Guatemalan President <PERSON> Vinicio </PERSON> <PERSON> Cerezo </PERSON> and later with the four foreign ministers. He contrasted what he described as democracy and growing prosperity in the four Central American nations with <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, where he said nine years of <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> rule and continuing warfare have virtually destroyed the economy. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has backed the Contras since 1981 in their fight to overthrow the Sandinista government. In <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> was trying to escalate action against his govermment. Speaking at a ceremony marking the ninth anniversary of the Sandinista air force Monday, <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said of the meeting: `` We hope that common sense might predominate, because to want to sign a death sentence against <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, because the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> wants one, would be the equivalent of signing a death sentence against <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>.'' `` We hope that these -LRB- Central American -RRB- governments might be sufficiently reasonable and pragmatic so as not to fall in the trap that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is laying in <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>,'' he added. The meetings in <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> were part of <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>'s quest for a united effort to isolate <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> politically and economically from its Central American neighbors. In a statement distributed to reporters in <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> City Sunday, the Honduran government said it found the demand for draft changes by <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> `` incomprehensible'' and `` strange'' and that the softening of its contents were at the insistence of those two countries. Eliminated from the original statement, the Hondurans said, were sections that would have: _ Criticized <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> for not separating its army, known as the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, from the governing political party _ Denounced `` subversion against <ORGANIZATION> democratic </ORGANIZATION> governments'' by <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> _ Called for a regional security system and continued consultation between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the four Central American nations <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Sunday that the original document had been drafted `` mostly ... by the Central American foreign ministers, not by us. Having drafted it, they were not so sure they wanted to issue it.'' President <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, who won the 1987 Nobel Peace Prize for designing and promoting the peace plan signed last Aug. 7, has promised his own progress report soon and there was speculation that his government decided the <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> declaration might undercut <PERSON> Arias </PERSON>' review. <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, unlike <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, does not share a common border with <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and pursues what it calls a policy of `` active neutrality.'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> was to fly on to <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> Monday night for his second stop on a 10-day trip that will take him to nine Latin American nations. He will return to <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> Aug. 8-9 for meetings with the presidents of <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>.
