weighing his choice of a running mate. And <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, whose reception was cordial but unenthusiastic received his only standing ovation when commenting on the vice president's absence from the meeting of the non-partisan group. Aides said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> could n't appear because of a prior commitment. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is to travel to <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> on Tuesday for a foreign policy speech, then make a trip to <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> later in the week before flying to his home in <LOCATION> Kennebunkport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, for the weekend. He is to address the Republican platform committee next Monday in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, one week before the party opens its national convention in that city. While Democratic senators worked in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to draft a compromise package of new aid to the Nicaraguan rebels, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> reiterated his opposition to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assistance to the Contras. `` It's a failed and illegal policy and it ought to stop,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said prior to leaving <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. `` Right now the administration once again seems to be doing everything again to ... destroy the peace process,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. The Democratic nominee said that, in principle, he does not favor humanitarian aid but would accept it if the aid was part of a negotiated settlement and the money was used to resettle the Contras and end the war. Democrats, in working on a new aid package, are trying to defuse an issue that has divided <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, who opposes Contra aid, from his running mate, <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, who has consistently supported it. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> insisted he was n't bothered by <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>'s support of Contra aid. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> spent most of Monday in private meetings in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in preparation for expected action this week on trade and plant-closing notification legislation. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, stepping up his efforts among the nation's black voters who earlier backed <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s presidential bid, said in his speech, `` We have to transform the cycle of poverty into a ladder of opportunity, and that ladder must be sturdy and strong for all our citizens.'' `` Some people say it ca n't be done,'' he said. `` I say we have n't tried.'' Then, using a rhetorical tool often employed by <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> accused the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration of spending vast sums of money on bad policies, following each contention with the refrain that at the same time `` we have n't tried'' to help minorities and others. `` Fifteen billion dollars already wasted on Star Wars. We have n't tried,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` Thirty-six billion dollars for two super-carrier task forces we do n't need and ca n't afford. My friends, we have n't tried. `` Hundreds of thousands of wasted lives, and millions of dollars to overthrow the government of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. My friends, we have n't tried `` An annual assault on the opportunity to go to college that has left us with fewer <PERSON> black </PERSON> college students today than we had seven years ago. We have n't tried.'' In <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, meanwhile, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, who lost the Democratic nomination to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, said Monday he is willing to meet with <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> to try and iron out differences dating back to <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>'s strong crticism of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> before <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s April primary. <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOC