<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said Monday he will announce D-Day, a date for a cease-fire in the 8-year-old Iran-Iraq war, after his fact-finding team returns from those countries this week and he consults the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. `` The D-Day does n't depend on the parties,'' the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> chief said, indicating he could make a unilateral decision and go ahead without the agreement of <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> says it is ready to honor an immediate cease-fire. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> made the statement to reporters after a three-hour meeting with Iranian Foreign Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Velayati </PERSON>. Announcement of a truce date would put pressure on <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> to compromise and drop its insistence on direct talks with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> before a cease-fire. No immediate reaction surfaced from <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> military team of experts now is in <LOCATION> Amman </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>, preparing its report, and the team leader will present it to him in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Wednesday. `` I will study his report. I will be in touch with members of the -LRB- Security -RRB- Council and then I will decide on a D-Day,'' <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said. `` It is very difficult to tell you now,'' he said when asked if he would announce D-Day this week. He cautioned against the idea that a cease-fire could be simply or rapidly implemented. The secretary-general said once D-Day is decided, he will begin consulting nations which could provide about 250 military observers to monitor the cease-fire and troop withdrawal. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> chief held his sixth meeting with <PERSON> Velayati </PERSON> since talks began last week. He has met three times with <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> Foreign Minister <PERSON> Tariq </PERSON> <PERSON> Aziz </PERSON>, but <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> said it was not prepared to enter into substantive talks with <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> until direct talks take place. Iraqi officials also have not responded to a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> report on chemical weapons which concluded that the <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> government has made frequent and large-scale use of the outlawed weapons against Iranian forces. <PERSON> Velayati </PERSON> and Ambassador <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Ja'afar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahallati </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> told reporters Monday that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> wants the secretary-general to go ahead and name the cease-fire date, with or without <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s agreement. `` <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> is immediately ready to implement -LRB- a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peace -RRB- resolution by a cease-fire,'' <PERSON> Mahallati </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said it was `` theoretically correct'' he could unilaterally announce a cease-fire date, `` but I prefer to wait for my team, be in touch with members of the council and perhaps the parties.'' He said he hoped for `` the shortest possible period'' between the announcement of a D-Day and the beginning of a cease-fire. The war, which began in September 1980, has cost an estimated 1 million lives. In response to questions, the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> chief said that if he or the council declared a cease-fire `` and one side does not respect it... that is for the council to decid