<TEXT>
 Gazing up at the sheer limestone north face of the Eiger, mountaineer <PERSON> Heinrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrer </PERSON> reminisced about the climb 50 years ago that changed his life. In July 1938, he and three other climbers became the first to scale the daunting 5,940-foot wall in the heart of the <LOCATION> Swiss </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alps </LOCATION> that is considered <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s greatest challenge to mountaineers. `` We were never afraid. We never had any idea of returning or giving up'' despite difficulties during the four-day adventure, the 76-year-old <PERSON> Harrer </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in a recent interview. Nine people had already died on the wall before <PERSON> Harrer </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fritz </PERSON> <PERSON> Kasparek </PERSON>, both Austrians, and <PERSON> Andreas </PERSON> <PERSON> Heckmair </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ludwig </PERSON> <PERSON> Voerg </PERSON>, both Germans, set out before dawn one morning to conquer the last virgin face of the <LOCATION> Alps </LOCATION>. Because of the danger, authorities had outlawed attempts to climb the north face. But the four defied the ban.
