<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Copenhill </PERSON>, a vine-covered slope with a nice view of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, is popular with people who cut swaths through <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. In 1864, Gen. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherman </PERSON> camped there during the battle for <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> before he burned the city and began his ruinous march to the sea. In the late 1960s, there was a plan to build a road through the area, and the state condemned and destroyed hundreds of homes to make way for it before the project was dropped. The Carter Presidential Center occupies it now and wants to build a road linking the complex to downtown <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. But the right-of-way sits empty and overgrown as neighborhood groups continue a battle over whether the road should be built. At one point, when construction started, workers shook protesters from trees. Today the fight is quieter. Court action has stopped construction since mid-1986. Opponents of the `` Ex-Pres. - Way,'' as they call it, have been in court for years saying the noise, fumes and road-widening would damage historic parks and neighborhoods including some designed by pioneer urban landscaper <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> The road also would slice through a public golf course. Road advocates argue the road was part of the presidential center package, that no more homes would be leveled, that it is needed for safety reasons and would lessen traffic through the older neighborhoods. They say the project would leave some <PERSON> Olmstead </PERSON> parks untouched and trim two only slightly. They note that court decisions have agreed with the need and with the environmental impact statements they have filed. Road opponents are awaiting word on whether the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> will hear their appeal. <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Adamson </PERSON>, lawyer for former President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> who also does work for the center, said that without the road part of the <ORGANIZATION> Carter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> could be reclaimed because the center got the use of 27 of the 30 acres of the library site from the state with the understanding that the road would be built. The argument has been used since the controversy began. `` It was n't true then and it's not true now,'' countered R.M. <PERSON> Ossoff </PERSON>, a leader of the anti-road movement. He said elected officials from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> senators to city councilmen are overwhelmingly in favor of the <ORGANIZATION> Carter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> but that political support for the road is dropping. `` Demonstrate to me how that much assembled influence could not resolve in three seconds any problems the Presidential Center might have,'' he said. The center already has landscaped the 27 acres at a cost of about $ 4 million. The road was meant to facilitate access to the Carter Presidential Center near downtown <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, and when <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> proposed the library he all but made the road a condition of the center being in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. Opponents of the proposed 2.2-mile Presidential Parkway say traffic through the area is short of predictions and that a smoothly operating <ORGANIZATION> Carter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> belies the claim that the center needs the road to function. Plans call for the four-lane road to have hiking trails, bike paths and other park facilities alongside it, and proponents say it actually will enhance the area. <PERSON> Olmstead </PERSON> designed <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s Central Park, the grounds of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capitol </ORGANIZATION>, the `` Emerald Necklace'' of parks around <LOCATIO