<HEAD>Do Cassandras Mismeasure the Economy?</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy is now in its 69th month of expansion, and according to a very popular view, three score and ten is time sufficient _ meaning the expansion should now roll over and die It is not a foolish concept, since aging expansions in years past have always developed deteriorations similar to the organic, muscular and osteo problems of human old age. But the concept is perhaps overly simple. The average post-war economic expansion has averaged 45 months, and ever since that average was surpassed two years ago the number of Cassandras has grown. They view further growth as bad, a recession as welcome. The reasoning is this: Factories are operating at near capacity and can not produce more; unemployment is down to the scraping-the-bottom level, and that means job openings can be filled only with less productive workers. Such measurements in the past have preceded inflation. Thus, a recession is inevitable, and the sooner the better, the pessimists argue. But some elements do n't seem to fit. `` Growth need n't be inflationary if it is based on solid productivity gains,'' says <PERSON> Prudential-Bache </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Yardeni </PERSON>, who believes some notions about economic expansions, rather than expansion itself, might be dated. Whereas the Cassandras fear that further growth will put too much stress on the system, <PERSON> Yardeni </PERSON> and some others observe that growth is what's needed to narrow the federal deficit. But what about the tight job market, ask the pessimists? To which those of more positive mind respond by calling attention to the billions of dollars industry is spending on more efficient plants and equipment, thus reducing the stress. In fact, economists of a positive bent point out, not all price increases are inflationary. Why, they remind us, a price increase accompanied by a bigger rise in product quality can actually be anti-inflationary. Surprised by the persistence of economic expansion in spite of their dire forecasts, some economists are now reviewing their basic notions. They concede there is no better proof or disproof than the economy itself. Incredibly, one factor that could explain the negativism is the neglect of the newer, service sector of the economy, while stressing the older industrial segment. Three-quarters of employment, 67 percent of gross national product and 90 percent of new jobs are in the service sector. Nevertheless, they figure less strongly in most analyses than do older industrial measurements. <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> and <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Layton </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> suggest that studies of the service sector do not always fit into neatly constructed concepts of what the economy should be doing. In short, there might be a built-in bias toward using industrial rather than service indicators. They contend that `` one reason for this is that many of the service industries have continued to grow during business cycle contractions as well as expansions.'' Therefore, `` indicators that skip recessions do not get a good rating, and hence tend to be rejected.'' <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> and <PERSON> Layton </PERSON> have developed service indicators for the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, financed by the <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION>. The first quarterly report has just been issued. In that report, economist <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinai </PERSON> analyzed the data and concluded there will be continued expansion in the service sector but at a somewhat slackened pace than had been so earlier in the expansion. His conclusion: `` Service-sector economic activity is continuing to expand nicely, but goods-sector activity is now driving the economy. `` The pace of services economics has softened compared with 1987, but does not pose any difficulty for the overall economy or job growth at this time.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Tuesday Aug 2</NOTE>
