<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, Aug. 8, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Woman's `Counterclockwise' Journey from Ad Exec to Counselor of
Poor</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA ROSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION> is a long way from <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION> but <PERSON> Annie </PERSON> <PERSON> Troy </PERSON> has made what she calls the `` counterclockwise'' passage, choosing sacrifice among the poor over affluence in the ad game. Ten years after she left <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> for the big city, Troy had risen to a $ 42,000-a-year job as creative supervisor of a large <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> advertising agency. She gave it up, and now, at 35, is executive director of <ORGANIZATION> Emmaus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a work and counseling program for about 50 formerly homeless people in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION>. She lives and works with them, subsisting on the same $ 25-a-week allowance that they receive. In a neighborhood where gunfire keeps her indoors at night, Troy spends much of her day running up and down stairs. Among walls hung with pictures of the Rev. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, the pale, slight redhead deals with everything from buying bathroom mirrors and supervising food deliveries to finding a new drug counselor. In the 18 months she's lived at <LOCATION> Emmaus </LOCATION>, Troy has come to miss her old neighborhood, her privacy and sometimes her old career. She misses shopping and seeing her friends. `` The little things can become a real big treat now, like getting together with a friend at a restaurant,'' she said. `` I enjoyed the freedom of being able to buy what I wanted. ... `` But it's also a freedom in saying ` OK, I think I have enough.''' Three years ago, <PERSON> Troy </PERSON> lost a friend to AIDS. Searching for a way to cope, she returned to church after a long break from her Lutheran upbringing. In a sermon one day at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> on East 16th Street, the priest discussed a man who established missions for the poor and an integrated <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> church in the 19th century. The man, <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Tyng </PERSON>, was Troy's great-great-great-grandfather. Her astonishment at the coincidence of hearing about her forebear in that church and her amazement at the breadth of his accomplishments sparked a change in her. As she sat there, she says, `` my eyes were opened to faith.'' `` Most people do n't need a religious experience,'' she said, `` but I guess I needed it to get my attention.'' <PERSON> Troy </PERSON> began to spend her free time helping with mostly administrative chores at a low-income housing construction project on <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>'s Lower East Side. After a month, they offered her a job as assistant director, at a pay cut of more than 50 percent from her advertising job. She accepted. Turning to the church had `` started my thinking going counterclockwise to where it had been,'' she said. `` It did n't seem like being competitive and making more money was really the thing to put my time on anymore. ... I just started to think ` if I'm going to work this hard, maybe I could work this hard on something that would really help people.' Father <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> founded <LOCATION> Emmaus </LOCATION> in 1966; two years ago it moved from a brownstone to what had been a hotel notorious for prostitution and drug-dealing. Arsonists gutted the building twice before <LOCATION> Emmaus </LOCATION> could move in. Now, <PERSON> Troy </PERSON> says, the dealers and prostitutes join the 250 people fed in <LOCATION> Emmaus </LOCATION>' soup kitchen each weekday. <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> talks of how much simpler and quieter life at <LOCATION> Emmaus </LOCATION> used to be, before homelessness and poverty intensified, before the advent of crack cocaine. For a woman reared in a small town near <LOCATION> Dayton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Emmaus </LOCATION> was full of revelations, despite what Troy already knew of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. A drug addict would come to her room for a friendly chat _ and leave with her watch. She felt betrayed until she sought guidance from a drug counselor, who taught her to look beyond the lies and manipulative behavior into the pain of a person bent only on getting their next fix. When people go to serve the poor, says Troy, they're full of romantic visions _ of rescuing lives, of finding a reward in grateful faces. They soon learn that the changes take longer, that successes are relative and that helpers, like those being helped, are only human. `` If you try to live according to that dream,'' <PERSON> Troy </PERSON> said, `` you get disappointed in yourself and in the others real fast.'' This spring, after six weeks of daily struggles to get out of bed, she recognized signs of the burnout that had hit her predecessor. She left for two weeks at a farm and <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> retreat in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, where people are trained to work with the poor and counseling is given to those who already do. On arrival they took one look at her tired face and put her in the infirmary. A month or so later, Troy looks weary again. She says she rarely thinks about returning to advertising, just occasionally when in a `` snit.'' But she wo n't try to predict where she might be 10 years from now. `` Ten years ago,'' she says, `` I never would have dreamed I'd be here.'' Though she stays in touch with her family and though her devoutly religious mother, in particular, supports what she does, one of the hardest adjustments to life at <LOCATION> Emmaus </LOCATION> was losing touch with her friends. Emergencies _ from a resident who's upset to a potential knife-fight in the soup kitchen _ often interfere with <PERSON> Troy </PERSON>'s outside plans, and her friends are reluctant to visit in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION> When they do get together, there are awkward first moments until they find themselves, once more, on equal ground. `` I guess there's something kind of odd,'' <PERSON> Troy </PERSON> said, `` about this friend who leaves it all to go to work with the poor'' and who becomes devout. But as she sees it, there can be as much stress in her old world as she has now. At <LOCATION> Emmaus </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Troy </PERSON> said, her religious conviction has been strengthened: `` There's so much that's beyond my ken or control, or anybody's ability to help.'' She turned to Roman Catholicism in October 1986, drawn by the church's devotion to the <PERSON> Virgin </PERSON> <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> and the accessibility of its weekday services. But her faith in human nature has suffered. `` I see the devastation that's happening with these people,'' she said, `` and I see on the other side people who are begrudging even giving out that dime to somebody begging. ... I really see that the problem is far more severe than I had ever thought.'' `` Then,'' she said, `` I have to turn to the individual for my hope.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Aug. 8</NOTE>
