<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, Aug. 10, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>In Home of Tabasco, `Hot Sauces are Almost a Religion'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY MacVEAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AVERY ISLAND, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Roll down the car window anywhere near the plant where <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s most famous hot sauce still is made from a century-old recipe, and your head just fills up with the scent _ a little tomatoey, a little spicy, a lot hot. The odor is so much a part of the place that <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> C.P </PERSON>. <PERSON> McIlhenny </PERSON>, whose family has been making Tabasco sauce from the start, does n't even notice it unless he's up close to the pulp barrels. Hot sauce in southern <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> is like that smell. It's everywhere On every table in every restaurant. Two dozen or so varieties. <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> hot sauce is a tourist attraction: It's on posters and coffee mugs and key chains, and people take tours of hot sauce factories. `` In the river parishes, where the Acadians first landed, its hard not to find a bottle of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> hot sauce on the table,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Folse </PERSON>, a chef and restaurateur in <LOCATION> Donaldsonville </LOCATION> who introduced Cajun food to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> during the summit meeting earlier this year. `` It's almost like salt, pepper and <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> hot.'' There is, of course, the theory that people who live in such steamy heat eat hot foods to perspire and cool off. `` My mother's people and my father's people grew hot peppers because they thought they were good for you,'' said television's down-home Cajun chef, <PERSON> Justin </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> But there's much more than science at work in a land where what to eat for dinner is often the focus of luncheon conversation and what to eat tomorrow is the dinner-table talk. Good food really matters here. `` When someone asks, ` What are you doing this afternoon?, You say, ` Oh I do n't know, maybe a crawfish boil.' They always think in terms of cooking,'' said <PERSON> Folse </PERSON>. And most everything _ even to a bloody <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> sorbet, says <PERSON> Folse </PERSON> _ gets a dash or two of hot sauce. `` I do n't think anything's worth a darn unless it's seasoned well,'' said <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, who is partial to cayenne peppers. <PERSON> McIlhenny </PERSON>, 44, vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> McIlhenny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, figures he goes through a 2-ounce bottle a month of Tabasco, which, by the way, is not a generic name, though <PERSON> McIlhenny </PERSON>'s pleased if you think so. Hot sauce is addictive, he said. `` I've had friends use it out of loyalty, and then say, ` Hey, this is good,' as if it was a surprise. They say they get addicted.'' So it's no surprise there are so many kinds _ Tabasco, <PERSON> Trappey </PERSON>'s, <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Cachere </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Creole </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hot </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sauce </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Crystal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hot </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sauce </ORGANIZATION>, Cajun Chef, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> Gold, <ORGANIZATION> Durkee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sauce </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Panola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Cajun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hot </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sauce </ORGANIZATION>. You get the idea. A premium sauce, it's agreed, uses only the pepper pulp. No seeds or skin. Most contain just salt, vinegar and peppers, although some labels say it fancier. Crystal, for example, lists `` fresh ripe aged peppers,'' and Cajun Chef contains `` select <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> cayenne peppers.'' So, can connoisseurs distinguish among them? Sure, said <PERSON> Folse </PERSON>, noting that most chefs stock four of five varieties. `` I've got items in my kitchen I use Tabasco on. However, I also really like <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> Gold,'' he said. `` I do n't find that it's quite as hot as Tabasco ... and when you have five or six chefs on the line, you want to have a little control If they put one shot or two shots, you do n't want to change the flavor competely.'' `` They all have a little different flavor, and they all use a little different amounts of vinegar, salt,'' said <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>. `` There are certain ones I prefer. ... It's just a question of experience, and God knows I have a lot of that.'' The <ORGANIZATION> McIlhenny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, too, has plenty of experience. Tabasco is sold in 100 countries; it's been on space missions. `` We end up in strange places,'' said <PERSON> McIlhenny </PERSON>. `` I understand two or three Sherpas in <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> will use a bottle at a single meal.'' <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> is a long way from tiny <LOCATION> Avery </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, 18 square miles that are home to 700 people, the Tabasco plant and fields, a salt mine and oil wells. There also are 100,000 snowy egrets, 30,000 azaleas and 17,000 irises. <PERSON> Avery </PERSON> <PERSON> Island </PERSON> is not really an island, but a salt dome that rises from the marshes and bayous on <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s Gulf Coast. At 152 feet above sea level, the island is the highest point along the gulf from <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. It sits 150 miles from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, separated by sugar cane, rice and oil fields. In 1818, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Marsh </PERSON> obtained rights to part of the island, and later a <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> judge, <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Dudley </PERSON> <PERSON> Avery </PERSON>, bought part. In 1837 <PERSON> Avery </PERSON> married <PERSON> Marsh </PERSON>'s daughter and eventually obtained the entire island. In 1859, <PERSON> Edmund </PERSON> <PERSON> McIlhenny </PERSON> married an Avery daughter. The story is told, though not verified, that the family fled <LOCATION> Avery </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> in the Civil War and returned to find everything destroyed _ except one defiant pepper plant grown from a seed or seedling given to <PERSON> Edmund </PERSON> by a friend returning from <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. What is known is that <PERSON> Edmund </PERSON> <PERSON> McIlhenny </PERSON> came up with a sauce to perk up the bland food available during Reconstruction. n 1868, he packed his invention in ladies' perfume bottles, and sent samples off to 350 wholesalers. Two years later he had a patent, and in two years more a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> office to handle all the European orders. His sauce used a variety of Capsicum frutescens, a small fire-engine-red pepper, of which the <ORGANIZATION> McIlhenny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> today is the world's largest producer. Tabasco is an Indian word for damp earth, which <ORGANIZATION> McIlhenny </ORGANIZATION> apparently chose because he liked the sound of it. One hundred twenty years later, little has changed. <PERSON> McIlhenny </PERSON> is still a family company, with <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> McIlhenny </PERSON> and two cousins in charge. And <PERSON> Avery </PERSON> <PERSON> Island </PERSON> is their kingdom. `` This is an ideal site,'' said <PERSON> McIlhenny </PERSON>. `` Part of the mystique is that only the soil, only the climate, only the nimble fingers of <LOCATION> Avery </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> could pick Tabasco.'' The peppers are harvested in summer, by hand, and must be processed the same day. But today, only 10 percent of the peppers needed are grown on the island. To protect against disease, pests, hurricanes and labor troubles, seeds for the rest of the peppers are sent to Central and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. The mash is returned to <LOCATION> Avery </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> McIlhenny </PERSON> inspects every white oak barrel of mash for aroma, color, particle size. He rejects one barrel in 100. The pulp is mashed with salt _ eight pounds to 100 pounds of peppers _ and aged three years. The mash is then mixed with a strong white vinegar and stirred mechanically for 28 days. Finally, it is strained and bottled. And even then it's not just a bottle of sauce. `` Hot sauces in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> are almost a religion,'' said <PERSON> Folse </PERSON>. `` You go to church on Sunday, hot sauce on Monday through Friday.''
</TEXT>
