<TEXT>
 On the other hand, <PERSON> Fulbright </PERSON>, a former chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, calls the hard-line <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> `` a great mistake.'' And in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, he says, `` We've always been so completely supportive of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> there's not much chance of a compromise.'' <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Ball </PERSON>, who held an important <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> post in the <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> administration, concurs. He faults <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> for `` inepitude'' in trying to work out a deal between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> in 1982 without consulting <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, and then ignoring President <PERSON> Hafez </PERSON> <PERSON> Assad </PERSON> for years because he did n't go along. <ORGANIZATION> Fascell </ORGANIZATION> credits <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> with toughness and willingess to lay his prestige on the line in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, `` although you ca n't say <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> was a success.'' There, 241 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> servicemen were killed in October 1983 when a Marine command center was blown up. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> peacekeeping forces, which critics said had been foolishly exposed, were then withdrawn. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Laitin </PERSON>, a longtime government press officer who worked for <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION>, tried to explain <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> this way: `` You have to remember the animal trainer describing how an elephant moves. He puts one leg forward, shifts his body over to that foot to see if it will hold him, then moves the next foot forward. He never leaves his moorings in one place without having another mooring. He's no great risk-taker.'' The ringing declaration, the apocalyptic pronouncement were not <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>'s style. He did n't convey the impression that the world's fate hinged on his success in persuading foreign leaders to support his policies For six years, plodding through U.S.-Soviet, <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> arms control diplomacy, he methodically recited to reporters, `` You do n't have an agreement until you have an agreement,'' which seems to echo baseball's <PERSON> Yogi </PERSON> <PERSON> Berra </PERSON>'s, `` It ai n't over till it's over.'' But if reporters found the secretary less than electrifying, neither did he play games with them, such as hiding behind `` background'' and not-for-attribution rituals in the ancient <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> tradition. He said what he had to say on the record, even when it meant admitting the failure of a high-stakes mission. And he persevered. He worked in behalf of Jews and other minorities who were prevented from emigrating from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. He made a point of giving human rights a `` pride of place'' on his agenda in all his sessions with Soviet leaders. He arranged meetings with dissidents in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and emigres in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> to lend symbolic support to their cause. Low-key team player that he was much of the time, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> could dissent sharply and publicly. He bristled at a White House order in 1985 to subject all government officials in sensitive positions to lie detector tests. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> would have none of it personally and threatened to resign unless the order was modified. It was. When <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> two years ago decided to sell subsidized wheat to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> called the sales `` ridiculous.'' Having led the opposition within the administration, he kept up his criticism after he lost. The Soviets, he said, must be chortling over paying less for American-produced food than American housewives. There was risk in such self-assertion. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Iran-Contras investigating committees, `` You must be willing to say goodbye, and I am.'' He had offered to quit on two other occasions. One was in 1983 when he discovered that <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> McFarlane </PERSON>, then the deputy national security adviser, had made a secret trip to several <LOCATION> Mideast </LOCATION> states without <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>'s knowledge. He said he told <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, `` Mr. President, you do n't need a guy like me for secretary of <ORGANIZATION> state </ORGANIZATION> if this is the way things are going to be done.'' The other came in August 1986 when <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> thought some conservatives in the White House subjected him to `` a kind of guerrilla warfare,'' to the point of hamstringing his authority to use government aircraft for his <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> business. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> served in the Marines in World War II and met his wife, <PERSON> Helena </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, where she was an Army nurse. They have five children and five grandchildren. When <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> asked <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> to succeed <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Haig </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> in June 1982, he was summoned from <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, where he had been on a business trip. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> was to meet with the president at Camp <PERSON> David </PERSON>, and he found two limousines waiting for him at the airport. One was for him, he was told, the other to take his wife wherever she wanted to go while he had his interview with the president. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> waved off the second car. `` No, she will come with me,'' he said. `` We are a package deal.'' He is the first man in history to have served in four Cabinet posts _ State, <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> _ 11 years in all of Cabinet service. A measure of his aptitude for conciliation and avoiding controversy is that he held three of these posts under <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> and emerged unscathed by any of that administration's notoriety and scandal. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Laitin </PERSON>'s theory, shared by others, is that while <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> is a team player, he also has a well-developed `` protective mechanism.'' `` It was not that he was fighting them all the time,'' says <PERSON> Laitin </PERSON>. `` There was an old-shoe relationship between <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> will go along, but at some point instinctively he'll hunker down He will not budge, because he's a man of character.'' As secretary of the treasury, he disregarded a <ORGANIZATION> Nixon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> request to have the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> harass `` enemies'' of the administration, provoking <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> to unflattering comments. And when <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> complained about an <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> audit of his tax return, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> told him that every recent president had been similarly audited. He showed no signs of winding down as his tenure neared its end. So far this year, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> has made four trips to the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, three to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, and a 17-day swing through <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. Why did he keep returning to the <LOCATION> Mideast </LOCATION> despite the refusal of Israelis and Arabs to heed his plea to negotiate? <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> explained he did n't mind fighting long odds, and if he did n't succeed himself, he wanted to lay some groundwork for his successor. Besides, he said, `` What am I saving myself for?'' End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 14
