<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 14</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 2 b&amp;w
photos. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ Was there ever a golden era of sports in the dim past, as touted by septuagenarian chroniclers? Maybe not, but there's one right now. It's the PGA Senior Tour, where golf's ancient rake in the lucre in post-career careers that lack the pressure and cutthroat solemnity of youthful competition but make up for it in sheer pleasure on the back nine of life
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By HUGH A. MULLIGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 At times the senior scene seems lifted live from the frame of an old Dutch golfing print, the whimsical kind you still find hanging in country club corridors and locker rooms. Genial gentlemen of mellowing vintage in broad-brimmed hats and knickerbockers bent over long crooked sticks in studious pursuit of nudging a small white ball across a pleasant expanse of lawn. Or perhaps these are Scottish shepherds who have lost their sheep in the Highland heather. Weep no idle Tennysonian tears for a vanished yesteryear. These are here and now maturing millionaires, some for the second time around, playing the PGA Senior Tour, sports' biggest success story in the past decade. `` It's a Mulligan on life, a chance for a second career at an age when all other athletes are over the hill,'' exulted the Australian <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Crampton </PERSON>, who made a million on the regular tour, retired to hunt oil in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> for eight years, then returned at age 50 to strike it rich again as a senior. In golf, a Mulligan is a second drive off the first tee, allowed in friendly circles to compensate for a dismal start, but purely illegal, even on the Senior tour where the over-50 set now competes in a friendly way for official prize money in excess of $ 10 million. The lucre is so lucrative that last year no fewer than a dozen seniors made more than in their regular career. At least a half-dozen more are poised to join <PERSON> Crampton </PERSON> and seven other seniors who already have won a million on the back nine of life. Here indeed is a new golden age of sport beyond the most avaricious dreams of the actuarial tables. The `` Old Sarge'' <PERSON> Orville </PERSON> <PERSON> Moody </PERSON>, recently matriculated to the millionaire class, is a splendid example of delayed golf growth. <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION>'s only win in 17 years on the regular tour was the U.S. Open in 1969. Prior to that, this part-Choctaw Indian spent l4 years in the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, rising to the envious rank of non-com in charge of golf installations. Joining the seniors, he tucked a 50-inch long putter, now affectionately known as `` the staff sergeant,'' tight unto his sternum and began pendulum stroking putts that now guarantee a more generous pension than the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> had in mind. In physical contour, <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION> more resembles Sgt. Snorkel in the Beetle <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> comic strip than your supple super jock. Senior millionaires come in all sizes, from the well-rounded <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Casper </PERSON> and <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> <PERSON> Barber </PERSON> to lean and hungry exercise fanatics like <PERSON> Crampton </PERSON>, a daily visitor to the physical fitness van in the parking lot, and <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Player </PERSON>, who still does 300 sit-ups a night on the motel floor. But even with the choice of riding in carts, is n't it hot work for chaps their age to be flailing away with woods and irons across seven miles of uncooperating landscape for the better part of a week? `` Playing golf is NOT hot work,'' demurs <PERSON> Chi </PERSON> <PERSON> Chi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON>. `` Cutting sugar cane for a dollar a day, that's hot work, hotter than my first wristwatch.'' <PERSON> Chi </PERSON> <PERSON> Chi </PERSON>, who took up golf at 25 cents a bag as a caddy in his native <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, managed to match in less than 30 months at senior play the million it took him 25 years to win on the regular tour. `` Anything is possible in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' says this jovial ambassador of the friendly, laid-back brand of golf that has made the senior tour such a hit with the galleries and TV audiences. Instantly recognizable in his straw fedora, <PERSON> Chi </PERSON> <PERSON> Chi </PERSON> finds time to chat with the fans behind the marshals' ropes, to autograph caps and sun visors and visit with kids and old people in wheelchairs. After sinking a 20-footer, he goes into his duelist act, wiping imaginary blood from his putter and seemingly sheathing it like a swordsman returning a sabre to its scabbard. Suddenly golf is fun again, in an age when so many younger players come across as unsmiling, monosyllabic, computer-programmed golfing machines, abandoning the color and drama to foreign players like the fiery Spaniard, <PERSON> Seve </PERSON> <PERSON> Ballesteros </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>'s `` Great White Shark'' <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Norman </PERSON>, and Masters champion <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON>, the slender <PERSON> Scot </PERSON> who deepened golf's mystique by revealing that his girlfriend cured his tensions by tickling his feet.
