 <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Player </PERSON>, the South African gold miner's son who at 50 found a new mother lode on the fairways, is convinced that in two years the senior tour will outshine the regular PGA circuit when enduring idols <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Nicklaus </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Trevino </PERSON> reach their semi-centennial. This Mulligan on life enabled <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Littler </PERSON> to put another million toward his hobby of collecting Rolls Royces after a bout with cancer almost ended a great career that at age 58 is still rolling in putts and prize money. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Mowry </PERSON>, whose `` best friend _ V.O. and coke'' betrayed him into dissipating early promise, joined Alcoholics Anonymous and came back with white hair and a steadier putting hand. He's become a consistent money winner among the seniors. Riding a golf cart has enabled <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Owens </PERSON>, the gutsy former paratrooper, to earn a half million in the senior game after four operations on his right knee, mangled in a jump at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bragg </LOCATION>. `` They're coming back from the dead; this is the greatest thing that ever happened in any sport,'' says <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Trent </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, the 82-year old golf course architect who still tees it up to test out his creations around the globe. All sorts of <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitty </PERSON> dreams are played out on the back nine of life. <PERSON> Walt </PERSON> <PERSON> Zembriski </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> steel worker who used to tiptoe out on skyscraper girders, is now walking on air in the top-20 senior money list. Among the born-again at 50 are <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, who spent l5 years in the auto repair business, and <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Boles </PERSON>, a former mortician. <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Terry </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Yankee </ORGANIZATION> righthander voted most valuable player in the 1962 World Series, smiles out from bubblegum cards and takes the mound at old-timers games at <LOCATION> Cooperstown </LOCATION>. But he's just a novice on the senior tour, not yet in the prize money class with <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Brodie </PERSON>, quarterback with the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> 49ers for l6 years, who turned to golf as a third career after a decade in the <ORGANIZATION> NBC-TV </ORGANIZATION> sports booth. Having your intellect scrambled by the likes of Big Daddy <PERSON> Lipscomb </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rosey </PERSON> <PERSON> Grier </PERSON> can be wonderful conditioning for golf's hard knocks `` I've been up by three touchdowns and forgotten to win,'' <PERSON> Brodie </PERSON> philosophized after blowing a two-stroke lead to <PERSON> Chi </PERSON> <PERSON> Chi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> at <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> in April. `` In golf you just wait until the end and add it up.'' Resilience of this sort enabled <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Ezinicki </PERSON>, former left-winger with the <ORGANIZATION> Toronto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leafs </ORGANIZATION>, to trade in his hockey stick for a persimmon wood and win the New England Seniors title. Pros getting a mite long in the tooth but shorter on drives competed long before the <ORGANIZATION> PGA </ORGANIZATION> formalized a seniors tour in 1980. In 1937, three years after he inaugurated the Masters, <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> of Grand Slam fame gathered some friends, including 23 <ORGANIZATION> Scots </ORGANIZATION>, eight Englishmen, two Irishmen and only four Americans, at <ORGANIZATION> Augusta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> for the first PGA Seniors Championship. The purse totaled $ 2,000, which was generous in an era when <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Snead </PERSON> got $ 45 a month to represent the <LOCATION> Greenbrier </LOCATION> resort on tour and <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Hagen </PERSON> tipped his caddy his entire check for winning the British Open, $ 240. <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> promulgated golf as a sport for all ages by installing a putting green on the White House lawn and assigning the <ORGANIZATION> Secret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to shag balls at <LOCATION> Augusta </LOCATION>. But senior tournament golf took off when <ORGANIZATION> NBC-TV </ORGANIZATION> in 1978 aired the finish of the first Legends of Golf from <LOCATION> Onion </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. The brainchild of producer <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Raphael </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Demaret </PERSON>, that unforgettable blithe spirit in purple saddle oxfords and polka-dot slacks, the Legends had going for it a $ 400,000 purse, a team format pairing the best of yesteryear and a thrilling three-birdie finale by <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Snead </PERSON>. The popularity of the Legends, which <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Hope </PERSON> dubbed `` The Prune Juice Open,'' prompted the PGA to add other senior events that soon attracted corporate sponsors. Now there are 37 stops on the Senior PGA Tour, including the Chrysler Cup, an international competition that recently spotlighted <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s 65-year-ld <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Vicenzo </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>'s 63-year-old <PERSON> Christy </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, and the <ORGANIZATION> Madza </ORGANIZATION> Champions, which pairs the cream of the oldsters with the best of the women pros in quest of a $ 500,000 team check Many other events outside the tour include a TV senior skins game, which featured 76-year-old <PERSON> Snead </PERSON>, and a growing foreign circuit that already stretches from <LOCATION> Rich </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Narita </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. Now that a golf course is being built at <LOCATION> Nachabino </LOCATION> outside <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, this capitalistic opiate of the aging masses is sure to spread to <LOCATION> Tbilisi </LOCATION>, capital of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, where the comrades reputedly live to 140 and beyond. In no time at all, Pravda will be covering the first Senior Centenary Classic.
