<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 On the lapel of his dark-blue school blazer, one <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> teen-ager wears a badge of <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>, founder of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. His classmate sports a button of <PERSON> Lennon </PERSON>, founder of the Beatles. Both are students at a school in the flatlands of southwestern <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Yevgeny </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yamburg </PERSON> is trying to encourage wide-ranging inquiry and tolerance to help children cope with the demands of modern Soviet society. In the three-story H-shaped building were <LOCATION> Yamburg </LOCATION> works as principal, 1,500 pupils and 76 teachers meet six days a week in split morning and afternoon sessions for the purpose of education. It is a business that <LOCATION> Yamburg </LOCATION>, 37, finds tremendously exciting. `` What we are trying to do is launch each child on an individual trajectory for his development,'' says the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> member, himself a son of teachers. `` Children are like barrels. Some you can fill up with just a little bit; others are bottomless. Each is different.'' Middle School No. 109, which sits in the middle of apartment high-rises, is a synthesis of the traditional in Soviet education and of the new possibilities now opening under Kremlin reforms. <LOCATION> Yamburg </LOCATION> says his is `` just an ordinary school,'' but <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> officials brought him to a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> news conference this year to talk about changes needed in education nationwide. `` You can go to him with any question and get a sensible, well-thought-out answer,'' says <PERSON> Tanya </PERSON> <PERSON> Litvinov </PERSON>, 15, a student at <LOCATION> Yamburg </LOCATION>'s school. `` He is open to us and to our problems.'' One middle-aged Soviet visitor found School 109 strikingly different from the schools he attended as a child. `` Most schools in this country are like military barracks. This one is different, and you see it right away.'' As <LOCATION> Yamburg </LOCATION> lopes through his school's strawberry-colored halls, children wish him good day, and he returns their greeting with a smile. In one classroom, 9-year-old girls in brown uniforms and white lace collars and boys in single-breasted blue blazers slowly repeat as teacher <PERSON> Yevgenia </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Potapov </PERSON> introduces them to the complexities of Russian spelling. Above the blackboard a red sign bearing the image of <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> proclaims: `` Lenin is even now more alive than the living.'' Up the stairs, a classroom of 15-year-olds openly disagree about the role of <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> in the Soviet past. `` He had a lot to do with the industrialization and collectivization of our country,'' says one blond-haired boy. `` Some consider him a criminal because he ruined our country's economic system,'' says another <LOCATION> Yamburg </LOCATION> relishes the debate. `` As someone who started life as a student of history, I feel my chief task is to form non-conformist minds, so that children are immune to mass manipulation,'' he tells a visiting reporter as he puffs on a Vietnamese-made cigarette. The principal, with graying temples, also teaches history nine hours a week, using recent newspaper and magazine articles because textbooks have been outpaced by the official criticism now leveled at <LOCATION> Stalin </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Yamburg </LOCATION> also assigns his students to compare historical accounts in Pravda, <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> and other Soviet newspapers and has discussed the strengths and weaknesses of socialism and capitalism with them. `` We try to raise children to see all sides of the problem, then to see the alternatives,'' <LOCATION> Yamburg </LOCATION> says. `` That's our ideal here.''
</TEXT>
