<FIRST>s e BC-APN--TVWeek Adv14   08-01 0869</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--TV Week, Adv 14,0891</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 14</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w
photo.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>

</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first time <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Selby </PERSON> kissed a girl on the stage his schoolmates teased him so relentlessly he almost quit acting. That was in the ninth grade. `` It took me a while to get over it,'' says <PERSON> Selby </PERSON>, who stars in the four-hour miniseries `` King of the Olympics: The Lives and Loves of <PERSON> Avery </PERSON> <PERSON> Brundage </PERSON>.'' While <PERSON> Selby </PERSON> temporarily gave up the theater, his faculty adviser at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> suggested that he enroll in an acting course. `` I took it and I've never looked back,'' he says. `` It was a lifesaver. It gave me such an outlook.'' <PERSON> Selby </PERSON>, who has spent a large part of his career on <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION>, is probably best known as <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Channing </PERSON>, the charming cad on the CBS prime-time soap opera `` Falcon Crest,'' In the new miniseries, which will be televised on the <ORGANIZATION> Harmony </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Premiere </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> in two parts between Aug. 15 and Sept. 15 on 85 stations, <PERSON> Selby </PERSON> has the title role as <PERSON> Avery </PERSON> <PERSON> Brundage </PERSON>. <PERSON> Brundage </PERSON> devoted more than 50 years to his dream of an Olympics that was free of political and economic influences. He was a controversial figure who made some enemies with his combative style and autocratic rule as president of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Olympic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. He participated in the 1912 Summer Games at <LOCATION> Stockholm </LOCATION>, but lost in every event to <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Thorpe </PERSON>. He hoped to participate again in 1916, but the games were canceled by World War I. In 1952, <PERSON> Brundage </PERSON> became president of the Olympics. The miniseries also reveals that although <PERSON> Brundage </PERSON> was married, he kept a mistress in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and had two children by her. `` They sent me the <PERSON> Brundage </PERSON> script and we talked back and forth,'' says <PERSON> Selby </PERSON>. `` The more I learned about <PERSON> Brundage </PERSON> the more I admired him and his energy and the way he raised himself up from his poor beginning. I loved his passion for the Olympics. It was wonderful to play a man with such a strong belief. `` We only had four hours, so we had to strike a balance between the Olympics and his personal life. His mistress, who's still alive, was interviewed for the series. `` <PERSON> Brundage </PERSON> became an engineer and builder who put up much of the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> skyline. He was a handball champion when he was 60. Doctors kept telling him he was overworking, and he kept saying that other doctors who had told him that were all dead.'' The series also stars <PERSON> Sybil </PERSON> <PERSON> Maas </PERSON> as his wife, <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON>, <PERSON> Renee </PERSON> <PERSON> Soutendijk </PERSON> as his mistress, <PERSON> Linnea </PERSON> <PERSON> Dresden </PERSON>, <PERSON> Kristoffer </PERSON> <PERSON> Tabori </PERSON> as his alcoholic younger brother, <PERSON> Chester </PERSON>, <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Starr </PERSON> as his mother, <PERSON> Minnie </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Shelagh </PERSON> <PERSON> McLeod </PERSON> as his secretary, <PERSON> Frances </PERSON> <PERSON> Blakely </PERSON>. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Philips </PERSON> directed from a screenplay by <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Wood </PERSON>. <PERSON> Selby </PERSON> was born and raised in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, where his family has a farm that has been in the family since 1660. `` The place was totally self-sufficient,'' he says. `` We r