<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 14</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>

</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> <PERSON> Clarke </PERSON> has some tips for the audiences watching her latest dream-like _ some would say nightmarish _ experimental theater production, `` Miracolo d'Amore.'' `` It should be looked at the way one listens to music or the way one would look at a symbolist or surreal painting, or interpreted the way one might a stream-of-consciousness poem, where it is highly imagistic and maybe metaphysical,'' says the show's creator. `` Miracolo d'Amore,'' which has 15 performers, played in May at the Spoleto Festival in <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, then opened June 14 at the off-Broadway Public Theater here. Most <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> performances have been sold out. Men wear the white costumes and tall caps of <PERSON> Tiepolo </PERSON>'s Punchinello drawings At the beginning, women are nude and playing a circle game denoting innocence. Their costumes make them look like flowers, based on sketches by <PERSON> J.J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Grandville </PERSON>. There is singing and talking, in pidgin Italian, embraces with a skeleton, loneliness, gang rape, fighting. `` I meant the title -LRB- `` The Miracle of Love'' -RRB- ironically,'' Miss <PERSON> Clarke </PERSON> says. Miss <PERSON> Clarke </PERSON> is known for experimental theater pieces, a succession of scenes, usually around an hour in length, inspired by art and culture, where theatergoers' ideas of what she `` meant'' vary widely. `` Miracolo d'Amore,'' is her least-literal, she says, and it may be her last. `` I think it's a difficult piece for people,'' she says. `` They ca n't come out being able to say exactly what it is. It has to be a subjective experience for the viewer, because it is an emotional work and it is a sad work. It's kind of a meditation on love gone wrong. `` The people who do n't get it at all are angered by it and dismiss it. I think it makes them frustrated. I'm afraid I always feel in trouble with people looking for literal or intellectual ideas in my work. `` Of the people who like it, somewhere it touches a deep emotional response in their own minds or dreams. People can be open to it and not feel they have to understand in a literal sense. Dreams have magic.'' `` The Garden of Earthly Delights'' in 1984 was Miss <PERSON> Clarke </PERSON>'s interpretation of a <PERSON> Hieronymous </PERSON> <PERSON> Bosch </PERSON> painting of heaven and hell It had dancers flying over the audience on wires. `` <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>: Lusthaus'' in 1986 showed the elegance and decadence, in which one might see seeds of fascism, of <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> at the turn of the century. `` The Hunger Artist'' in 1987 was taken from starvation in <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Kafka </PERSON>'s writings and emotional starvation of his life. Miss <PERSON> Clarke </PERSON> started `` Miracolo d'Amore'' a year and a half ago. `` It went in an unpredictable direction,'' she says. `` You never know where they're going till you've gotten there. I read a lot of <PERSON> Italo </PERSON> <PERSON> Calvino </PERSON> fairy tales, to be inhabited by <PERSON> Punchinellos </PERSON> and these flower fairies. The stories were very dark, horrifying, funny _ and impossible to translate to stage. I gave up on them real quickly. And <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> seemed glutted with fairy tales at the time. `` Then I just started working with my company in improvising themes on primal emotions. There are elements of fairytale in it but fractured and shattered.'' She is n't working on another one. `` I do n't want to do this any more,'' she says. `` It's not a matter of success or failure. It's a matter of my own growth not to stay still and repeat. I want to explore and direct opera next. I want to get into film directing _ specific, literal stories. I'm now ready to go linear.'' In July, she went to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to talk to <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> about possibly doing movement for a co-production planned by the Glyndebourne Opera Festival and the <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> Grand Opera. `` It is a discussion, not a job, at this point,'' she says. Miss <PERSON> Clarke </PERSON> studied modern dance at the <ORGANIZATION> Juilliard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, was a member of <PERSON> Anna </PERSON> <PERSON> Sokolow </PERSON>'s dance company for three years, then the Philobolus Dance Theater from 1972 to'78. She founded her own dance company, <LOCATION> Crowsnest </LOCATION>, before moving into experimental theater. She lives in <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, divorced from sculptor <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Grausman </PERSON>. Her son, <PERSON> David </PERSON>, is 19 and studies jazz composition. `` Garden,'' probably her best-known work, was revived off-Broadway in 1987. It has been on tour and will tour again next year. `` <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>'' will tour this fall to <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
