<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Books and Authors: An Endless Number of Possibilities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 There are no sure things in <PERSON> Bobbie </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>'s stories, just endless possibilities `` I think in terms of possibility. It's part of my heritage,'' said <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, whose second novel is called `` Spence + Lila'' -LRB- <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> and Row, $ 12.95 -RRB-. <PERSON> Spence </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lila </PERSON> <PERSON> Culpepper </PERSON> are a couple in their 60s who live on a farm in western <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>. They are brought together with their three children, <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON>, <PERSON> Catherine </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, when <PERSON> Lila </PERSON> is diagnosed as having breast cancer and must undergo surgery. <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, a native of western <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, contrasts the lives of <LOCATION> Spence </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Lila </PERSON>, who have spent most of their lives on the farm, to those of the children, who have moved away. `` It's a very confusing time for people of that -LRB- the children's -RRB- generation,'' the author said. `` They're subject to so many influences and problems because of all the choices. They can get divorced; their parents could n't do that. So many influences, so much more money.'' While the children move around the country trying to find themselves, <PERSON> Spence </PERSON> is perfectly happy to stay on the farm. `` There's a passage where <PERSON> Spence </PERSON> is looking around the farm and thinking that everyone is breaking their necks trying to get something grand,'' <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> said. `` For Spence, it's right here, on the farm. The basic facts of the universe are here: birth, growth and death. `` It is extraordinary to plant soy beans and harvest them.'' <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, born in 1940, can relate well to the Culpepper children. She grew up on a dairy farm near <LOCATION> Mayfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, and was the first member of her family to go college, taking journalism classes at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION>. She has also done her share of moving. After college, she lived in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and went to graduate school at the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Binghamton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, and the Uny
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 ty of <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>. She now lives with her husband in rural <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>'s independence and thirst for adventure was inspired by the movies her parents took her to see as a child. `` They saw movies, but they did n't have the sense that they could just take off and go to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and go where the movies are,'' she said. `` It seemed possible for me to go out there.'' The radio also had an impact on the author. `` I first listened to rhythm and blues in the late'40s and early'50s,'' <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> recalled. `` That struck a very deep chord in me _ one of those formative things. I certainly had the longing and curiosity and wanting to experience new things. `` That's why I have <PERSON> Spence </PERSON> as a rock' n' roll fan.'' <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>'s first story was published in 1980. Two years later, she released `` Shiloh,'' a collection of short stories that won the PEN-Ernest Hemingway Award for first fiction. In 1985, she came out with her first novel, `` In Country'', the story of <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>, a teen-ager trying to learn more about her late father, a <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> soldier killed before she was born. `` In Country,'' was a best seller. A film adaptation, starring the English actress <PERSON> Emily </PERSON> <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> as <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Willis </PERSON> as her uncle, is in progess. <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> writes sparely, leaving much of the interpretation to the reader. She has been compared to such contemporary writers as <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Beattie </PERSON> and <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Carver </PERSON>, who have been called minimalists. While <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> admires <PERSON> Carver </PERSON> and <PERSON> Beattie </PERSON>, she rejects the idea of consciously emulating them. `` One does n't like to identify with labels. That means that you agree that you're part of a movement,'' she said. `` That's just me. I think in a certain decade; lots of people are going to sound similar.'' Describing <PERSON> Lila </PERSON>'s thoughts the night before her operation, <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> uses short, almost telegraphic sentences: `` Lila ca n't sleep. Random scenes pass before her eyes. The strong, comfortable smells of cows in the barn waiting to be milked, the steamy air in winter. Gathering in tomatoes before a frost. Sprinkling lime on the potatoes spread out on the ground in a stall of the barn. Laying the onions on screen-door racks above.'' <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> notes that the real meaning of her stories can be learned from the pacing of her writing, rather than the words themselves. `` Hardly anybody points out those things. The sentence rhythms mean everything because they create the tone and the voice and the characters.'' For `` Spence + <PERSON> Lila </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> sought to create a delicate mood. `` I wanted it be very calm and reflective and tender and deep. To go way inside. It's a love story.'' That's why she put a plus symbol in the title. After <PERSON> Lila </PERSON>'s surgery, she and <PERSON> Spence </PERSON> return to the farm. The books ends with this passage in the garden of <LOCATION> Spence </LOCATION> observing <LOCATION> Lila </LOCATION>: `` The way she laughs is the moment he has been waiting for. She rears her head back and laughs steadily, her throat working and her eyes flashing. Her throat catches her finally and slows her down, but her face dances like pond water in the rain, all unsettled and stirring with aroused possibility.'' `` Somebody said to me that the word ` possibility' is the key,'' <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> said of the ending. `` Possibility is what there is.''
