<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Aug 12-14 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Vanwarmer Album `Like Gathering Your Family'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Singer-songwriter <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Vanwarmer </PERSON> is counting on the emotional edge of his new album to stem a nine-year slide since his million-selling hit `` Just When I Needed You Most.'' The 33-year-old <PERSON> Vanwarmer </PERSON> has just released `` I Am,'' a collection of soft country ballads with romantic titles such as `` I Will Hold You,'' `` That's What Your Smile Does for Me'' and `` Words I Never Meant.'' It's his first album in four years. `` There's something spiritual about the record,'' <PERSON> Vanwarmer </PERSON> said in an interview. `` It's kind of like gathering your family around the fireplace.'' As a marketing exercise, however, it has been a disaster. Instead of <PERSON> Vanwarmer </PERSON>'s `` It's a Heartache,'' a tune by pop-jazz singer <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Franks </PERSON>, `` The Camera Never Lies,'' was distributed erroneously with <PERSON> Vanwarmer </PERSON>'s name printed on it. The mistake was repeated during a second round of distribution, so record company officials gave up on the song and will switch to another one, `` Where the Rocky Mountains Touch the Morning Sun.'' `` The radio stations kept calling and saying, ` We like <PERSON> Randy </PERSON>'s record but he's not country enough for our station,''' <PERSON> Vanwarmer </PERSON> said `` His record is kind of jazz, funky, but we have similar textured voices. I can almost understand why they almost thought it was me.'' His tough luck continues a pattern since his powerful `` Just When I Needed You Most'' propelled him from obscurity in 1979. Instead of establishing himself as a ballad singer, he followed up with an uptempo tune titled `` Got ta Get Out of Here.'' `` It did terribly,'' <PERSON> Vanwarmer </PERSON> recalled. More than half a dozen singles were released subsequently, but none was a hit. On the advice of others, he declined to do American concert tours that would have built up his name and following. A possible tour with <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> was bypassed. Furthermore, his record company wound down, `` and I do n't think they were putting the money behind the records that they needed to,'' he said. `` I do n't blame anybody,'' he said about the downfall. `` Maybe if I had been more knowledgeable. ... `` We had one solid record, and then we wanted to change direction _ something with a little more edge. I wanted to do it; that was just naivete. My first record seemed so easy. I do ballads best. We could have done another ballad, but we put out an uptempo thing.'' Though he failed to capitalize on the success of `` Just When I Needed You Most,'' he says his royalties from writing the hit paid the bills for six years. His breakup with his girlfriend inspired the song. `` That was kind of devastating,'' he recalled. Six months later, he sat down and put the song on paper. `` I found that those kind of songs, the deepest ones, come some time after an event. You're too traumatized at the time. When someone leaves, you just do n't go sit down and write a song. If you did, you'd almost wish bad things would happen to you.'' He said the song was a hit because listeners related to a lament over a broken romance. `` It's happened to everyone. That emotion is universal. Some people like to feel sorry for themselves,'' he said. `` I always hoped the record was n't wallowing in self pity and it had some redeeming value, and I guess it does.'' A footnote about the song is that <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sebastian </PERSON> of the rock group <ORGANIZATION> Lovin </ORGANIZATION>' Spoonful played autoharp on the record. `` To me, it was one of the things that sold the record,'' <PERSON> Vanwarmer </PERSON> said. In 1980, he wrote the song `` It Never Hurts to Hurt Sometimes,'' which later became a No. 1 hit for the Oak Ridge Boys. The song, triggered by the death of his father 13 years earlier, made its way to the charts in an unusual fashion. The song got into the hands of <ORGANIZATION> Oak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ridge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boys </ORGANIZATION>' record producer <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Chancey </PERSON>, whose wife fell in love with it after hearing it on a demonstration tape. It was then recorded by the group as a favor to her, <PERSON> Vanwarmer </PERSON> said. `` One perk of being a songwriter is exorcising your feelings as they come along,'' he said. `` And people can exorcise theirs as they listen too.'' He wrote it on Christmas Eve as he sat alone at home before gathering with family members. `` It was emotion from the heart. It wrote itself.''
</TEXT>
