<HEAD>Victims Of Pollution Seek Toxic-Free Homesites</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VERO BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Pressinger </PERSON>'s troubles began when he was teaching in a portable classroom built with particle board. His chest hurt, he could n't concentrate and he was depressed. He had frequent colds and an abnormally low white-blood cell count, indicating liver malfunction. Doctors could n't determine a cause for his symptoms. <PERSON> Pressinger </PERSON>'s suffering became so intense he finally left his girlfriend and gave up his job. He joined the <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> and went to teach in <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>, but had to leave after a year because the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> began using a strong pesticide in the classrooms in which he taught. Suspecting sensitivity to chemicals, he began sleeping on a beach to escape the smells of pesticides, disinfectants, paint, and even perfume. Pressinger, 33, is one of a growing number of people who believe they are severely allergic to chemicals, victims of environmental illness. Doctors, however, ca n't agree on what is causing symptoms that have led some sufferers to seek a `` toxic free environment'' by giving up their jobs and moving to the desert or even going so far as to seal their rooms with aluminum foil linings. `` Much of what is attributed to environmental factors can only be theorized,'' says Dr. <PERSON> Phillip </PERSON> <PERSON> Lieberman </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, clinical allergist and president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Allergy </ORGANIZATION> and Immunology. `` So there is great controversy as to whether the precepts of the physicians practicing environmental medicine are valid, at this time.'' The burden of proof `` belongs on the physicians practicing the specialty,'' <PERSON> Lieberman </PERSON> says. Dr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Rae </PERSON>, a cardiovascular surgeon who also specializes in clinical ecology, says, `` Nothing is 100 percent proven. But most of the debate occurs out of ignorance ... It's a scapegoat for not looking into it critically.'' <PERSON> Rae </PERSON> contends that 10 percent to 20 percent of the population suffers from such sensitivity. His clinic in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> says it has treated 17,000 people for environmental illness in the past dozen years. Some of them are sensitive to formaldehyde in particle board, paneling and rugs, others to food or gasoline. Even the smell of deodorant, vehicle exhaust, newsprint, clothes, bedding and other everyday substances can cause reactions. Pressinger lives at his mother's home here, doing everything he can to avoid contact with chemicals. He believes his only real escape is a secluded, uninhabited island. He has checked out properties in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, and now is trying to get enough sufferers together to buy an island in the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION> which is untainted by pollution. The island he's found is 2 -LCB- miles long and a half-mile wide about 5 miles from <LOCATION> Abaco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. Its asking price is $ 4 million and <PERSON> Pressinger </PERSON> says it could be subdivided for sale just to sufferers of chemically caused illnesses. `` This type of arrangement would allow complete control of the surroundings without the risk of unexpected chemical exposures. We've got to find someplace. It's not a matter of if, but when.'' <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, who heads the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> for the Chemically Hypersensitive, in <LOCATION> Wrightsville </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, says the group is interested in a chemical-free environment. `` We feel the need is for an inexpensive, long-term rehabilitation oasis for the environmentally ill and their families.'' <PERSON> Pressinger </PERSON> also has taken his idea to the Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ecology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>, which publishes a magazine, runs educational campaigns about the problem and helps sufferers find treatment. <PERSON> Rae </PERSON> is one of its directors. `` In the beginning, I thought I was the only one that had such problems,'' says Pressinger. `` The initial reaction of doctors is that it's a psychological problem. It's a complex illness that is little understood, even by physicians. `` There are many people out there who have it and do n't even know it.''
</TEXT>
