<HEAD>Researcher Says Prairie Dogs A Problem But Misunderstood</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TENA HARALDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIOUX FALLS, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ranchers say prairie dogs do n't live up to that cute-sounding name. Prairie rodents is more like it, they grumble of the furry animals that chomp grass and booby-trap pastures with their burrows. Zoologist <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoogland </PERSON> admits the critters cause problems but says they're basically misunderstood. Much of what he says flies in the face of lore. `` Prairie dogs will expand unless they are controlled, said <PERSON> Verne </PERSON> <PERSON> Brakke </PERSON>, director of regulatory services for the state <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. Not so, said <PERSON> Hoogland </PERSON>. In fact, in a behavior pattern observed in fewer than a dozen other species, prairie dog mothers leave their own pups unguarded to enter the burrows of female relatives where they kill and eat the babies. `` The implications of this are enormous,'' he said. `` There seems to be a system in which the prairie dogs are controlling themselves.'' <PERSON> Hoogland </PERSON>, of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION>, has been watching prairie dogs in one colony in Wind Cave National Park since 1975, and the population has stayed around 150. `` That colony has not expanded 1 inch,'' he said. The killings at first went unnoticed because they occurred in burrows, then <PERSON> Hoogland </PERSON> noticed that females visiting other burrows would emerge with blood on their fur. The evidence was uncovered when a burrow was excavated. `` Fifty-one percent of all litters are killed by infanticide,'' he said, adding that the common perpetrator is a female relative, though in a few cases the mother turns on her own litter. Litters average two to three pups. `` The leading candidate is that they are doing it for food,'' he said. `` I have never seen them eat any other meat. `` Maybe in other colonies there are certain things we could do to make the prairie dogs control themselves.'' Ranchers wo n't shed tears over the deaths of prairie dog pups. Since the 1800s, when pioneers and their cattle moved west, it's been war `` Back in the early 1900s at one point the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government hired 125,000 people whose only job was to eradicate prairie dogs,'' <PERSON> Hoogland </PERSON> said. Those efforts continue today in states like <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Brakke </PERSON>. Most states have animal damage offices, but anti-prairie dog efforts are not coordinated from state to state. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> had 800,000 acres of prairie dog towns in 1980. Today that is down to 250,000 to 300,000, <PERSON> Brakke </PERSON> said. No figures are available on the amount of land infested nationwide, but millions of acres are involved, he said. `` They are a rodent. We give them kind of a cute and furry little attribute, so we call them prairie dogs. If we called them prairie rats or prairie rodents there would n't be that connotation,'' he said. `` I grew up with a dislike, a distaste and an aboslute hate for prairie dogs,'' said state Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Marvis </PERSON> <PERSON> Hogen </PERSON>. `` The bread of life in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> is grass, and those little buggers eat grass, and the second thing is they make holes that your horse can step in and break his leg.'' <PERSON> Hoogland </PERSON> said it's hard to find examples of that, and added, `` Everybody hates prairie dogs but almost nothing was known about them. Ranchers say, ` Look what they've done to my land,' but there's a lot of evidence that prairie dogs move into areas that have already been overgrazed. `` I'm not saying there's no competition -LRB- with livestock -RRB- but I'm saying all the evidence is n't in yet Two hundred years ago there were jillions of prairie dogs and jillions of buffalo, so they could coexist.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>End of Adv for Aug. 4</HEAD>
