<HEAD>Georgia Tech Computer Models Say Wall Street Headed For Another
Big Tumble</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock market will be ready for a major fall, similar to the one in October, if interest rates go any higher, according to a <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> professor. `` It looks in a sense like'88 may be a replay of'87 as it relates to the stock market,'' said <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Allvine </PERSON>, a management professor who based his forecast on computer analyses of the economy. With factories operating near capacity and unemployment at a 14-year low, `` you see the possibility of inflation breaking out all over, the genie getting out of the bottle,'' said <PERSON> Allvine </PERSON>, who has headed <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION>'s stock marketing forecasting project for nine years. Four of <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION>'s five market computer analyses `` have reached a negative threshold which has been associated with ultimate downturns on the market,'' <PERSON> Allvine </PERSON> said. `` Last year the economy was running very strong, there were inflationary concerns and the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- was compelled to hold a steady course on liquidity, which ultimately led to the very speculative stock market,'' he said. `` Our numbers on our <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> models are showing that both the short-term and long-term -LRB- interest -RRB- rates are becoming very close to where they were a year ago at this time,'' <PERSON> Allvine </PERSON> said. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> is snugging up in terms of its action to see that the economy does not run away,'' he said. `` If this does not work and interest rates continue to rise, there could be another crumble in the stock market.'' Inflation has been a major concern of the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>, which tries to keep the economy stable by manipulating the supply of money in circulation. The gloomy analysis is based on the fact short term rates are higher, with the federal funds rate, the interest for overnight borrowing by banks, as high as it was on Oct. 19, the day of the crash, <PERSON> Allvine </PERSON> said. The fed funds rate, which stood at 7.625 percent when the market collapsed, was quoted at just over 7.75 percent on Friday. `` Other interest rates are up sharply from the beginning of the year, and some are higher than at the time of the crash,'' <PERSON> Allvine </PERSON> said. In 1987, the prime rate rose from 7.75 percent in March to 9.25 percent two weeks before the market crashed. It stands now at 9.5 percent. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s discount rate, the interest rate it charges member banks for loans, was increased from 5.5 percent to 6 percent a month before the crash and remains at that level.
