<FIRST>r f BC-China-EnterpriseLaw     08-01 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-China-Enterprise Law,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Enacts Law Giving More Power to Enterprises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> on Monday enacted a law that ends direct state controls over enterprises and gives factory managers greater freedom over their operations. The introduction of the enterprise law came with warnings that factories will no longer be able to live off state largess and will face bankruptcy if they fail to respond to market competition. The law, passed by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last April, gives factory managers greater autonomy over planning and personnel and makes them responsible for profits and losses. It is to be followed in November by enactment of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s first bankruptcy law, which will set down rules for shutting down insolvent plants. Legalization of the manager responsibility system, already widely practiced in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s state-run factories, has been hailed as a major step in the government's drive to reduce the role of central planning and make industry more efficient by linking its production to market-determined supply and demand factors. <PERSON> Zhang </PERSON> <PERSON> Yanning </PERSON>, deputy minister of the state commission for restructuring the economy, said last week government departments that previously exercised direct control over industries should abide by the principle of `` the state regulates the market, which in turn guides the enterprises.'' Several years of experimenting with the manager responsibility system, however, has proved the difficulty of following that principle. Factory managers are still at the mercy of state allocations departments that control disbursement of scarce and increasingly expensive energy and raw materials. Managers told they now must make profits are also thwarted by irrationally low state-set purchasing prices for many of their products. Approximately one-fourth of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s state-run enterprises are operating in the red, and the number is increasing with recent sharp increases in the costs of raw materials. The People's Daily, the official voice of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said in a front-page commentary Monday that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s 10-year-old economic structural reforms have `` entered a critical stage.'' Enterprises can no longer harbor the illusion that the state will provide low-priced raw materials and subsidies to cover losses, it said. Banks will not be a certain source of low-interest loans. Factories must move aggressively to reform their management, personnel, organization and income distribution systems because in the future `` market competition will be relentless.'' `` There will certainly be some enterprises that will fail in the competition and be declared bankrupt,'' the newspaper said. Under the new law, enterprises will have the right to sell products on their own after meeting obligations to the state, and to choose their own suppliers, set product prices and negotiate and sign contracts with foreign parties. Senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON>, the mastermind of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s economic reforms, first suggested an enterprise law in 1978, but it was not until this year that disagreements over the relationship among the state, the manager and workers were finally worked out.
</TEXT>
