<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Corn and soybean futures soared their permitted daily limits at the opening today on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> as hot, dry weather returned to the drought-stricken <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. Wheat and oats also were sharply higher. After a two-week reprieve, the hostile weather has returned with the soybean crop in the midst of its most critical growth stage, analysts said. `` The next two to three weeks are going to make or bake the soybean crop, and it looks like we're going to bake it,'' said <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Lespinasse </PERSON>, a trader with the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. Dry heat is expected to persist in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> for most of this week and that could mean another round of sharp price increases in the crop futures markets, analysts said. Most contracts for future delivery of corn and soybeans opened up their respective daily limits of 15 cents and 45 cents a bushel. The August soybean contract, on which the limit has been removed pending the contract's expiration later this month, was up more than 70 cents in early trading. Also in early trading, wheat was 12 cents to 17 cents higher with the contract for delivery in September at $ 3.83 a bushel; corn was 15 cents higher across the board with July at $ 3.05 \ a bushel; oats were 10 cents higher across the board with September at $ 2.81 -LCB- a bushel; soybeans were 45 cents to 71 cents higher with August at $ 8.47 a bushel Most cattle futures were sharply lower while pork futures were sharply higher to limit-up in early trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle w