<NOTE>$adv 06</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Aug. 6-7 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Kruses Cruising Along On Top of Classic Car Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS P. WYMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUBURN, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When fashion designer <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Lauren </PERSON> set his heart on a pair of racy Ferraris, he made one quick telephone call to <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>. Many of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s richest car buffs do the same. Displayed on the office walls of <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kruse </PERSON>, the man who answered <PERSON> Lauren </PERSON>'s phone call, are photographs of actors <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Kercheval </PERSON> and <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Piscopo </PERSON>, pro football lineman <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Bosworth </PERSON>, hotelier <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Marriott </PERSON>, and former senator and White House chief of staff <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>. In his late 20s, <PERSON> Kruse </PERSON> is president and owner of <ORGANIZATION> Kruse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, one of the nation's most exotic auction houses. Founded by his father, <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kruse </PERSON>, the company has come to dominate the classic car market at a time when values have skyrocketed. With the dizzying prices in the classic car arena, would-be buyers of modest means are likely destined to remain would-be buyers. `` We deal with such wealth that a guy can get excited and caught up, and it does n't matter that he just spent $ 100 for what most other people think's worth $ 10,'' said <PERSON> Kruse </PERSON>. His figure of $ 100, of course, is figurative. Top models such as Duesenbergs routinely fetch $ 1 million and more. The record belongs to a 1931 <ORGANIZATION> Bugatti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Royale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merline </ORGANIZATION>, which brought $ 6.8 million in 1986. Last year, the Kruses coaxed bids of $ 152 million on about 10,000 automobiles. The business started in 1971 at <ORGANIZATION> Auburn </ORGANIZATION>'s annual weekend car festival. <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Kruse </PERSON>, a successful local auctioneer of real estate and household goods, noticed many of the old cars carried for-sale signs. So he stepped in and set up an auction. `` We had a rope as a gate, and 3,500 people paid $ 1 to get in, and another 3,500 jumped the rope,'' said the younger <PERSON> Kruse </PERSON>. `` A man turned down $ 35,000 for his <ORGANIZATION> Duesenberg </ORGANIZATION>, which was just unheard of because they were selling for about $ 5,000 to $ 10,000 at the time.'' The auction became an annual Labor Day weekend event and sales jumped. Their calendar takes the Kruses across the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, with auctions in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION>, as well as major sales in <PERSON> Reno </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Nev. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. `` We've really developed <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> as a market in the last couple of years because of the incredible wealth down there,'' said <PERSON> Kruse </PERSON>. The Kruses claim to hold 75 percent of the market. Wherever they go, their sales technique does n't vary much from the manner that sells low-price household goods at a farm auction. Sell the sizzle, the Kruses say, not the steak. `` You can have a frying pan, and go ` One dollar, two dollar, three dollar,''' said <PERSON> Kruse </PERSON>. `` Or you can say, ` Oh, I can smell my grandmother's fried chicken in there right now. Who'll gim me $ 20?''' <PERSON> Kruse </PERSON>'s picks for today's best bets to become the classics of the future include the limited edition <ORGANIZATION> Buick </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> GNX </ORGANIZATION>, Mustang convertibles, Corvettes, the IROC-Z Camaro, maybe the <ORGANIZATION> Cadillac </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Allante </ORGANIZATION>, and the Avanti, created by <PERSON> Studebaker </PERSON> designer <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Loewy </PERSON> and now in limited production under owner <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>. The keys to collectibility are condition, design, horsepower and historical significance, <PERSON> Kruse </PERSON> said. People seem to value notoriety more than wholesome fame. `` Usually if a bad guy owned it, it's worth more than if a good guy owned it,'' he said. Does it seem like there are limitless numbers of <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> staff cars? <PERSON> Kruse </PERSON> says there are more than 20 of the Mercedes 770-K models, many protected by armor plate and bulletproof glass, that might be touted as <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s personal car. `` If -LRB- reich marshal <PERSON> Hermann </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Goering </PERSON> even looked at it, it's a <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> car,'' <PERSON> Kruse </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
