<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Officials from the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> confirmed Monday that a meeting of the cartel's price monitoring committee would be held Aug. 3 in <LOCATION> Lausanne </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. The confirmation of the date, which had been tentatively set, came in the wake of a visit to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> by <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON>. The five-nation price monitoring committee, made up of the oil ministers of <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Venzuela </LOCATION>, is empowered to study the situation on world oil markets and can also call an extraordinary meeting of all 13 <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> member countries' oil ministers. <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> officials hope to stabilize the cartel's price fluctuations and runaway overproduction now that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> are negotiating to end the eight-year-old <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> war. The last ministerial meeting, held in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> in June, failed to unify the cartel on the pricing and production issues. The next <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> ministerial meeting is scheduled for December.
