<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: An AM version is planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar finished mixed against other major currencies in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> on Monday. Trading was light and the dollar stayed in a narrow range, dealers said. Gold prices fell, with markets quiet due to a Swiss national holiday. Traders in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> said early attempts to push the dollar to new highs met with fears of central bank intervention and profit-taking. `` Everybody's worried about the central banks,'' said a trader for a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bank. `` I still think there will be an attempt to set higher levels,'' on Tuesday, he added. Some traders said the dollar's failure to break new ground suggested that it may have to drop back and establish a bottom before proceeding higher. `` Having just come off the highs and heading down ... it looks a bit more vulnerable on the downside,'' a trader said. Corporate customers, meanwhile, `` just are n't around'' owing to summer holidays, another trader said. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound rose to $ 1.7130, compared with $ 1.7105 on Friday. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where the business day ends as <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s begins, the dollar rose 0.72 yen to a closing 133.25 yen. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at the lower rate of 132.75 yen. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late Friday: 1.8758 West German marks, up from 1.8750; 1.5615 Swiss francs, unchanged; 6.3255 French francs, up from 6.3202; 2.1145 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1185; 1,381.50 Italian lire, up from 1,377.75; 1.2075 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2105 Gold fell in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a bid price of $ 433.75 a troy ounce, compared with late Friday's $ 435.25. <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION> was closed for a Swiss national holiday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell 87 cents to close at a bid $ 436.70. Silver was quoted late Monday in <LOCATION> London </LOCATI