<HEAD>Boeing Profits Up 36.8 Percent In Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Higher sales and lower expenses and taxes helped boost <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s second-quarter profits 36.8 percent over the same period of 1987, the Seattle-based aerospace company said today. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> reported net earnings of $ 160 million or $ 1.05 a share on sales of $ 4.71 billion, compared with profits of $ 117 million or 75 cents a share on sales of $ 3.48 billion a year ago. For the first half of 1988, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> had profits of $ 296 million or $ 1.94 a share on sales of $ 8.32 billion, up 26 percent from first-half 1987 profits of $ 235 million or $ 1.51 a share on sales of $ 7.24 billion. In a news release, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> chairman and chief executive officer <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Shrontz </PERSON> attributed the brighter performance to increased sales volume; lower levels of research and development and other new business costs for computing, electronics and military and space programs; and lower federal tax rates. But <PERSON> Shrontz </PERSON> said the gains were offset somewhat by `` significant performance problems'' on several military airplane programs; increased research and development and production costs at <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>'s deHavilland commuter plane division; and having to bear a larger share of expenses on government contracts <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> enjoyed record orders of $ 13.3 billion for commercial planes in the second quarter, with 23 customers ordering 268 jets and 29 turboprop commuter planes. That compares with orders totaling $ 7.6 billion for second-quarter 1987. For the six months ending June 30, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> had orders for 397 jets and 35 turboprop planes valued at $ 18 billion. In the same period of 1987, there were 208 jets and 34 prop planes ordered, worth a total $ 11.1 billion. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> is expected to have its fourth straight year of record orders for commercial jets. The company, however, does not receive payment for planes until they are delivered, which can be years after the orders were entered. Military sales in the first half totaled $ 2.4 billion, $ 200 million less than in the same period of 1987. <PERSON> Shrontz </PERSON> said military sales for 1988 are expected to be slightly less than last year.
