<HEAD>Construction Spending Inches up 0.1 Percent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for digest item slugged AM-Construction Spending.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Construction spending inched up 0.1 percent in June as a big increase in investment for new factories helped offset declines in housing and government projects, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. Building activity rose to a seasonally adjusted, but not inflation-adjusted, annual rate of $ 402.8 billion in June, following a 0.8 percent increase in May. Construction spending for the first half of 1988 was only 1.3 percent above the January-June period of 1987, lagging behind the 2.0 percent rate of inflation in construction costs between the two periods. Analysts had been expecting even greater weakness, predicting office and hotel construction would decline in response to high vacancy rates. But projects are getting built anyway. `` What is happening is ... there is a lot of money available, from here and overseas,'' said economist <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Sumichrast </PERSON>, who heads a consulting firm in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Different aspects of the same phenomenon are fueling both the increase in factory investment, which rose 5.7 percent in June and stands 21 percent higher than it was a year ago, and the growing availability of money for other construction projects. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturers are spending more on new equipment and building projects to meet higher demand for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> goods overseas. They're finally benefiting from the fall in the value of the dollar between early 1985 and the end of 1987, which made <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> goods cheaper on foreign markets. However, although the trade deficit is not as bad as it was, foreigners still collect more dollars than they need to buy <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> goods and thus look for ways to invest that money. The Japanese, particularly, prefer to invest surplus dollars in government securities and real estate, rather than in other investments such as corporate stock. `` There's one good -LRB- real estate -RRB- deal for every 50 that you bring to the table, but the money has to be put someplace. ... I'm afraid we're going to continue to build in some areas where we should n't really build,'' <PERSON> Sumichrast </PERSON> said For the rest of the year, analysts are expecting a continued softening of construction activity, led by weakness in housing, which is being hurt by an upward creep in mortgage interest rates. Residential construction fell 0.9 percent in June to an annual rate of $ 188.1 billion, the third decline in a row. A 0.7 percent drop in construction of single-family homes more than offset a 2.3 percent increase in apartment construction. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Savacool </PERSON>, an economist with the <ORGANIZATION> Wefa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> in <PERSON> Bala </PERSON> <PERSON> Cynwyd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, said factory construction will likely strengthen and residential building wane through the rest of this year. However, he said, if the recent appreciation in the dollar, which has rebounded somewhat from its lows at the end of last year, continues, it could choke off the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturing boom and dampen the main area of construction strength. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> offered these details of construction spending in June: _ Non-residential private construction climbed 2.5 percent, the fourth consecutive monthly increase, to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $ 99.2 billion _ Hotel and motel construction increased 19.4 percent after falling for two months Analysts said the category swings widely from month to month because one or two large projects can skew the total. _ Construction of office buildings was off by 0.4 percent from the May level However, the small decline followed increases in May, April and March, and the June rate was still 12 percent higher than a year earlier. _ Shopping center and other commercial construction was unchanged from May _ Government construction projects fell 1.4 percent in June to an annual rate of $ 78.6 billion with highway construction, the biggest segment of the government sector, suffering a 1.6 percent decline
