<HEAD>US Export-Iport Bank Resumes Lending to Brazil</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government's <ORGANIZATION> Export-Import </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> announced on Monday that its board of directors has agreed to resume lending to <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> to encourage sales of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> goods there. The action follows an agreement reached in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> over the weekend between <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and 13 creditor governments, including the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. This accord will delay repayments on $ 5 billion worth of debt falling due between Jan. 1, 1987 and March 31, 1990. <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Amaral </PERSON>, head of the <LOCATION> Brazilian </LOCATION> delegation, said that none of the interest or principal will be repaid until the end of that period. Payments will then be spread over 10 years. It is unusual for such arrangements to delay payments of both interest and principal. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bank announced on July 11 that it was accepting applications for loans to <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and that a decision would be made after the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> talks. `` This condition has been satisfied and <ORGANIZATION> Eximbank </ORGANIZATION> now is prepared to act on preliminary and final commitments,'' said the bank's president, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bohn </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, in a statement <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s international credit was badly hurt in February 1987 when it stopped paying interest on more than $ 60 billion of its bank debt, the biggest in the Third World. It now has an agreement with a committee representing its bank creditors to delay payments on about $ 62 billion, and to take new loans of $ 5.2 billion from the banks to help pay them the back interest. The committee is collecting approvals from over 600 creditor banks for this arrangement. The <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>, owned by 151 governments, has said it will also lend <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> more money when the banks have agreed.
