<HEAD>Crop Futures Skyrocket As Hot Weather Returns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soybean, corn and oat futures skyrocketed their permitted daily limits Monday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> amid fears that a new heat wave in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> will do further damage to drought-stressed crops. Wheat futures also closed sharply higher. The return of hot, dry weather to the Corn Belt after a two-week reprieve holds a particular threat to the soybean crop, which is in the middle of its critical pod-filling stage, analysts said. High temperatures _ 95 degrees or higher _ are more detrimental to soybeans at this growth stage than lack of moisture, said <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> <PERSON> Feltes </PERSON>, director of commodity research with <ORGANIZATION> Refco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a large, Chicago-based commodities brokerage house. Temperatures soared into the upper 90s Monday afternoon in the central Corn Belt states of <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> and the hot, dry weather was expected to persist for most of the week. `` If these high temperatures continue, we're looking at a potentially serious shortfall in soybean production, even with the recent rains in the eastern Corn Belt,'' <PERSON> Feltes </PERSON> said. Most contracts for future delivery of oats, corn and soybeans closed up their respective daily limits of 10 cents, 15 cents and 45 cents a bushel. The August soybean contract, on which the limit has been removed pending the contract's expiration later this month, closed more than 60 cents higher. At the close, wheat was 9 cents to 15 cents higher with September at $ 3.81 a bushel; corn was 13 -RCB- cents to 15 cents higher with September at $ 2.90 a bushel; oats were 10 cents higher across the board with September at $ 2.81 -LCB- a bushel; soybeans were 28 -LCB- cents to 64 cents higher with August at $ 8.40 a bushel.
