<FIRST>r f AM-TelevisionRatings Bjt   08-01 0781</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Television Ratings, Bjt,0803</SECOND>
<HEAD>AGB Suspends U.S. Television Ratings Service</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> AGB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> is suspending its <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> television ratings operation, saying it underestimated the costs of competing with audience measurement leader <PERSON> A.C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nielsen </PERSON>. The disclosure disappointed some advertising and television industry executives, who said <ORGANIZATION> AGB </ORGANIZATION> had provided some competition in the national TV ratings arena that has been dominated for 30 years by <PERSON> Nielsen </PERSON>. `` They had breathed some life into what had been an inactive portion of the business,'' an executive of a major advertiser said Monday, speaking on condition he not be identified. But others said <PERSON> Nielsen </PERSON> still faces potential competition from companies such as <ORGANIZATION> Arbitron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ratings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which has announced plans to launch a national TV ratings service over the next few years that also will monitor buying habits. AGB, a limited partnership in which the British concern <ORGANIZATION> AGB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> had a major interest, is widely credited _ or blamed, depending on the view _ with encouraging use of `` people meters'' in measuring national TV audiences. The people meter is a handheld device that not only electronically records when the television is on, but permits viewers to push buttons to record exactly who is watching at any given time. After years of use in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> AGB </ORGANIZATION> decided to employ the devices as it launched its <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> television ratings operation in the fall of 1987. <PERSON> Nielsen </PERSON> had been testing its own people meter, and announced it would rely on the device for its 1987-88 ratings as well. Under its old system, <PERSON> Nielsen </PERSON> used a combination of meters to measure when sets were on and handwritten diaries to tell who watched particular shows. Critics of the old system said an explosion in viewing choices made it increasingly unrealistic for anyone to record accurately in a diary what everyone in the family watched. But others said the people meters have shortcomings as well, such as in measuring viewing by children. `` If it had n't been for AGB coming into the market with their people meter, I do n't think <PERSON> Nielsen </PERSON> would have come out as soon with their people meter,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Otter </PERSON>, a senior vice president at the advertising agency <ORGANIZATION> McCann-Erickson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Worldwide </ORGANIZATION>. But the cost of the ratings service was more than AGB had expected. The London-based <ORGANIZATION> AGB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> said it had estimated in April 1987 that it would cost $ 49 million for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> service, but that within a year the complexities of the market had driven costs past $ 67 million. `` Following discussions with the TV networks, advertising agencies and advertisers, it became clear that despite considerable support, the prospects for future revenue would not make the project viable and would be unlikely to cover the increased level of costs,'' the company said. This past spring, <ORGANIZATION> AGB </ORGANIZATION> approached the three major television networks in an effort to get all three to sign up for this fall and beyond. <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> had been the only major network to subscribe to the AGB ratings in the 1987-88 season, and getting <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> to join was seen not only as a way to boost revenue for <ORGANIZATION> AGB </ORGANIZATION> but also as a signal to advertisers and their agencies of the prospects for the service. `` It is disappointing to have one of the competitors gone,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Sonkin </PERSON>, vice president for network audience research at Capital Cities-ABC. But he said <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> decided against subscribing because of the cost. Asked for a response to <ORGANIZATION> AGB </ORGANIZATION>'s announcement, <PERSON> Nielsen </PERSON>'s chairman and chief executive, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Holt </PERSON>, said, `` Our operating assumption that the television audience measurement business is a competitive one remains unchanged.'' At <ORGANIZATION> Arbitron </ORGANIZATION>, spokeswoman <PERSON> Nan </PERSON> <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> said the AGB decision will have no effect on that company's plans, which call for introduction of a system that monitors both viewing and buying habits in five major markets in the fall of 1989 and expansion into a national system in the fall of 1990. She noted <ORGANIZATION> Arbitron </ORGANIZATION> has been measuring local audiences in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for years and has a long-term commitment to a national service. In announcing <PERSON> Arbtron </PERSON>'s plans in June, Arbitron Presdident A.J. <PERSON> Aurichio </PERSON> said he expected <ORGANIZATION> Arbitron </ORGANIZATION> would lose $ 125 million on the syswtem over four to five years before breaking even in 1995. In announcing the suspension of its television ratings service, <ORGANIZATION> AGB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> also announced it would acquire <ORGANIZATION> Mediamark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which measures magazine audiences, in an exchange of stock. <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON>, chairman of Mediamark, said <ORGANIZATION> AGB </ORGANIZATION>'s choice of the word `` suspension'' in describing the status of its <ORGANIZATION> AGB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> operation in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was deliberate, leaving open the possibility that it could be resurrected in another form at some future date.
