<HEAD>South Africa Bill Would Cost Americans $1.2 Billion, Survey Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> investors could lose $ 1.2 billion on their shares in South African gold mining stocks if legislation requiring Americans to sell all their investments in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> becomes law, a report said Monday. The legislation introduced by Rep. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Dellums </PERSON>, D-Calif., is intended to bring pressure on <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> to end its system of apartheid, in which the black majority has no voice in national affairs Americans would lose money because the legislation would force them to sell at depressed, `` fire sale'' prices, the study said. The report was based on economists' models of the interaction of supply and demand. The study was conducted by the <ORGANIZATION> Wefa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a consulting firm based in <PERSON> Bala </PERSON> <PERSON> Cynwyd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, on behalf of <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a New York-based mutual fund that invests in precious metals mining stocks and has about 40 percent of its assets in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Americans owned $ 4.5 billion in South African mining shares as of the end of 1987, and of that, $ 3.2 billion was in gold mining shares, making it the single most popular South African investment for Americans, the study said. International Investors estimated that about 500,000 Americans own shares in gold mining stocks. The study did not attempt to calculate overall losses to American investors if the bill became law. A Dellums spokesman, <PERSON> R.H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, said the congressman believes negative effects of the bill would be temporary because the end of apartheid would free the South African economy from its `` state of siege.'' The legislation is sponsored in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> by Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass.
