<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> ended a six-month power struggle Monday with settlement of lawsuits over their proxy fight earlier this year. As part of the settlement, <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> will buy back an estimated 16 million shares at $ 45 each, or a total of $ 720 million. The deal also contains a `` stand-still'' agreement, under which <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> said it would not buy significant numbers of <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> shares, participate in any proxy contest or otherwise seek control of the company for three years. The settlement ends <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION>'s suit stemming from the April 21 proxy vote it lost to <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION>. As a result, the personal care products giant does not face a rerun of the election. A federal judge said last month he was inclined to order a new vote because <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> misled stockholders in an advertisement about <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> before the election. Industry analysts have said a rematch would have strengthened <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION>'s hand. Under terms of the settlement, all <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> stockholders may sell one share back to the company at $ 45 for each seven they own. <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> officials estimated the total number of shares likely to be purchased under the settlement agreement are about 16 million of the approximately 112 million outstanding shares. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Froelich </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Pershing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said that the settlement means that <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> management `` wants to keep the status quo. But they're shrinking the capital and diluting earnings a bit.'' After <ORGANIZATION> Revlon </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Perelman </PERSON>'s failed bid for <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> in 1986, <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> paid $ 558 million to buy back 9.2 million shares of stock. But <PERSON> Froelich </PERSON> said the company will be able to continue to fight off such takeover attempts `` as long as they keep the earnings rising and they have. I do n't think the stockholders will be too badly off.'' <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> stock plunged $ 2.62 -LCB- a share to $ 37.50 in composite trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION>, which owns nearly 6 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> stock, forced the proxy vote earlier this year in hopes of winning four directors' seats to pressure the 12-member <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> board to sell the company. <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> believes a sale would boost the value of <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> stock. <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> filed suit April 14 seeking to block <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION>'s proxy bid on the grounds that <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> falsified <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> filings and di not fully disclose all investors. A countersuit filed by <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> five days later alleged <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> misrepresented <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> in advertisements and mailings to the company's 27,000 shareholders and failed to publicly disclose all companies that had expressed interest in buying <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Court Judge <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> ruled in early April that <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> inaccurately portrayed <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> in newspaper advertisements leading up to the proxy vote in which shareholders rejected a <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> slate of four dierctor candidates. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Tierney </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> general partner, issued a statement saying: `` We believe this settlement at this time is in the best interests of all concerned.'' <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzgerald </PERSON>, spokeswoman for <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION>, maintained that `` all shareholders will benefit'' from the repurchase agreement and said it was not dissimilar to a buy-back plan announced by the company for shareholders in 1986, prior to the <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> action.
