 The stock market finished mixed Monday but largely resisted traders' sporadic efforts to cash in on last week's sharp gains. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which surged 68 points last week, inched up 1.78 to close at 2,130.51. Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 11-to-9 in nationwide trading of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> Exchange-listed stocks, with 830 issues up, 672 down and 481 unchanged. Volume on the floor of the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> came to 138.17 million shares, down from 192.34 million in the previous session. Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trading at regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market, totaled 157.84 million shares. Stock prices opened mixed and seesawed in a narrow range. While traders wondered whether last week's gains could be sustained, analysts were divided over just how healthy the day's trading shaped up to be. Some were encouraged that the market held its ground. `` The market is holding rather tenaciously to -LRB- last week's -RRB- gain,'' noted <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Metz </PERSON>, vice president and technical analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Oppenheimer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` It is absorbing profit-taking with relative ease.'' A stronger bond market and a rise in the Dow's key transportation sector helped support equities. But other observers, pointing to anemic volume and a lack of a conviction, were not so satisfied. `` All last week's rally did was recover losses from the prior week,'' said <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Peroni </PERSON>, a technical analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Janney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Montgomery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scott </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. He noted that stocks moved to `` the upper end of their trading range and then ran out of momentum.'' Those who appeared pleased with the day's events said they would have been far more concerned had the market's upward move resumed at a brisk pace. `` What you do n't want to see is instant euphoria,'' said <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wachtel </PERSON>, first vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. A measured approach to the market could mean better things down the road `` That's the kind of action you get prior to a trend resuming,'' <PERSON> Wachtel </PERSON> said. Among actively traded <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> issues, <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> was down 2 | at 37 -LCB-; the razor-blade maker reached a stand-still agreement in its legal dispute with <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> and said it will buy back 16 million shares for $ 45 each <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>, which reported higher quarterly earnings, was up 1 ~ at 62 -RRB- Armtek jumped 4 \ to 42 Mark IV Industries, which holds 14.9 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Armtek </ORGANIZATION>, intends to offer $ 40-a-share for the company. Central & amp; <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, the most active issue with 19.7 million shares changing hands, was up -LRB- at 31 -LCB-. Traders were interested in capturing the company's dividend. Elsewhere, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> was up -LCB- at 126 \, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> was up 1 at 29 -LRB-, and <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> was off | at 44 -RCB- As measured by <ORGANIZATION> Wilshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>' index of more than 5,000 actively traded stocks, the market gained $ 3.25 billion, or 0.12 percent, in value. The <ORGANIZATION> NYSE 