<HEAD>NV Philips Restructures U.S. Operations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> NV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Philips </ORGANIZATION>, the Dutch electronics giant, Monday named a new chief executive at <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Philips </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and split off $ 1 billion worth of peripheral operations into an independent subsidiary. <ORGANIZATION> Philips </ORGANIZATION> said the changes, which will take effect Sept. 1, were intended to `` further integrate the <ORGANIZATION> Philips </ORGANIZATION> organization in the <LOCATION> U.S.A. </LOCATION> into the global activities of the company.'' <ORGANIZATION> Philips </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s largest electronics company and the world's No 1 television manufacturer, last week reported a 44 percent decline in its second-quarter profit. It blamed foreign-currency losses and competition from <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. Named to be chairman and chief executive of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Philips </ORGANIZATION> was <PERSON> Gerrit </PERSON> <PERSON> Jeelof </PERSON>, who will continue as executive vice president and vice chairman at the parent company, based in <LOCATION> Eindhoven </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Cees </PERSON> <PERSON> Bruynes </PERSON>, who has held the top post at <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Philips </ORGANIZATION>, will become the chairman and chief executive of a new subsidiary, <ORGANIZATION> Consolidated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Philips </ORGANIZATION> said. The new subsidiary will include the Magnavox defense contracting business, which had to be kept independent of the Dutch-based company because of <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> rules. It will also include a variety of peripheral businesses ranging from Anchor Brush toothbrushes and Genie garage door openers to <ORGANIZATION> Selmer </ORGANIZATION> musical instruments and Magnavox cable television equipment. The creation of <ORGANIZATION> Consolidated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> should not be considered a prelude to the disposal of some of the businesses in it, said <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruttner </PERSON>, a vice president at <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Philips </ORGANIZATION>. The operations to be included in the new subsidiary accounted for about $ 1 billion of <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Philips </ORGANIZATION>' 1987 revenue of $ 5.5 billion and about 15,500 of its 59,000 employees. <ORGANIZATION> Philips </ORGANIZATION>' brand names include <ORGANIZATION> Philips </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Norelco </ORGANIZATION>, Magnavox, Philco and Sylvania.
