<FIRST>r f AM-DefenseProbe-Consultants     08-01 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Defense Probe-Consultants,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pryor Bill Would Require Registration of Consultants</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Private consultants to defense contractors would have to register with the federal government under provisions of a bill introduced in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> on Monday by Sen. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ark </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON> chairs the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Government Affairs federal service subcommittee, which has held a series of hearings on the use of consultants by <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> contractors. `` The bill is intended to shed some sunshine on the all-too-shadowy world of consultants. Bringing everything into the light should cut down on the shady dealings,'' said <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON>. He was referring to the current investigation that focuses on allegations that contractors' consultants, many of them former <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> employees, paid bribes to current <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> workers for inside information about contracts. No charges have yet been filed. Federal officials testified to <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON>'s subcommittee that they did n't know specifically how much was being spent on consultants. In part, that lack of knowledge comes from the fact that contracts do n't have to detail services provided by consultants. <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON>'s bill would create a registry of consultants and no consultants could be hired unless they were registered. That registration would require detailed information about the identity of a consultant's clients along with the services provided by the consultant. The bill would also detail a new category in federal budgets, requiring government departments to list the amount they spend on consultants.
