<HEAD>RepublicBank Rescue Part of NCNB's Aggressive Nature</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> came to the rescue of ailing <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> RepublicBank </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, it was doing what came naturally _ aggressively expanding into new markets. `` The single biggest strength of this company is we have a ` do business' attitude,'' <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> vice president <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Middlemas </PERSON> said Monday. `` We try to do something with every deal that comes in. Maybe we do n't do it as it's presented, but we try to do it. `` It's part of our culture _ our strength,'' he added. `` We're quite prepared to go there -LRB- <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> -RRB- and do business. As he spoke, some 250 <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> managers were in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> taking control of the 41 banks that made up the insolvent <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> RepublicBank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, now operating as <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. On Friday, <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> _ currently the nation's 18th largest bank with $ 28.6 billion in assets _ was selected to acquire the financially ailing <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> bank in what has been described as the largest bank rescue in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said it would spend up to $ 4 billion to bail out <LOCATION> First </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> but expects to recoup a large portion of those losses. <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> was created in 1960 when <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Charlotte </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Greensboro </ORGANIZATION> merged. The new bank had $ 480 million in assets, 1,300 employees and 40 offices in 20 <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> cities and towns. In the next two decades, <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> grew rapidly through mergers with existing banks and by opening new offices. It also gained a national reputation for aggressively pursuing new markets. In 1981, <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> purchased <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>. Federal law had barred a bank from operating in more than one state, but the merger was approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> because <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> had owned a trust company in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> since 1972, before the state enacted laws prohibiting the takeover by out-of-state companies Observers say <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION>'s venture into <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> sparked a five-year buying spree that tripled it's assets to nearly $ 29 billion. Once allowed to capitalize on opportunities in other states, <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> bought up banks in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. Former <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. President <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Dougherty </PERSON> said the latest move reflected the same strategy that opened the door to interstate banking seven years earlier `` If we had n't been aggressively interested in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, we would n't have ever gotten in,'' he said. <PERSON> Middlemas </PERSON>, who is in charge of the company's <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> banking group, said the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> deal `` is a big step in ensuring <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION>'s survival in banking circles for a long time. Size is important.''
