proposal to extend cooling off period.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> issued a compromise offer Monday in an effort to avert a strike by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> that could affect 41,000 commuters and disrupt freight deliveries in several Farm Belt states. Separately, Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, D-Ill., said he planned to introduce legislation to speedily extend a cooling-off period in the labor dispute for 36 days, which would postpone any strike action The railroad offered to accept a recommendation by a presidential emergency panel to eliminate 700 brakemen's jobs, instead of the 1,150 cuts <ORGANIZATION> C </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; NW had previously said were needed. But <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> general counsel <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> said the union was not impressed by the offer. `` That wo n't settle it,'' <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> said. C & amp; NW spokesman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Foote </PERSON> said the railroad `` made a concessionary offer to the union to try and settle this dispute.'' But he acknowledged the railroad is `` not very hopeful'' the union will accept the offer to avert the strike, scheduled to begin Thursday. The recommendation initially came from the <ORGANIZATION> Presidential </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> in July, which President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> appointed in April in an effort to solve the longstanding dispute, <PERSON> Foote </PERSON> said. Until Monday's compromise offer, <ORGANIZATION> C </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> NW </ORGANIZATION> had said it wanted to save $ 51 million a year by cutting most of its train crews from four to two people, eliminating what it considers unnecessary brakemen's jobs and leaving an engineer and conductor on board The union has considered that move unacceptable. The presidential panel recommended that all the railroad's freight trains be operated with three brakemen instead of four, that only two brakemen be used on certain nonstop freight trains, <PERSON> Foote </PERSON> said The strike would affect commuters in a six-county area around <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> for whom C & amp; NW provides service through an agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Metra </ORGANIZATION>, a suburban commuter rail service. It would also affect freight service in several Midwestern states. However, neither side can act until a cooling-off period ordered by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> ends at 12:01 a.m. on Aug. 4. <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> said Monday's move by the <ORGANIZATION> C </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; NW was intended to persuade <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> not to extend the cooling-off period. `` C & amp; NW does n't want'' the strike to be postponed, he said. `` They want it to come to a head. `` All the purpose of this statement is to persuade <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> not to take any action,'' <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> said. But in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Carle </PERSON> said an extension of the cooling-off period would give both sides `` breathing room'' to come up with a solution on their own. He said <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> would introduce the bill under a `` fast-track'' procedure that would allow a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> vote Tuesday, and would work with several <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members who could get it through that chamber the next day.
