 Butcher & amp; Singer, <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>'s largest independent brokerage firm, is being acquired by Wheat, <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Richmond </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, the two companies announced Monday. The terms were not disclosed. The merger is the culmination of talks that began two months ago and were prompted partly by <ORGANIZATION> Butcher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Singer's interest in Wheat's computer operations, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> McElroy </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive of Wheat, <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> McBee </PERSON> <PERSON> Butcher </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive of <ORGANIZATION> Butcher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Singer, which has roots going back to the American Revolution, said both parties would like to have the merger completed by the end of September. `` I think that everyone is enthusiastic about it because it makes you much more of a contender when you're this size,'' <PERSON> Butcher </PERSON> said. Butcher also said the privately-held firm was being sold to cut costs and to boost efficiencies. The merger will eliminate about 100 of the firm's 500 jobs in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, he said. Butcher and other executives from the firm will become officers of <ORGANIZATION> WFS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION>, the Richmond-based parent of Wheat, <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>. However, top levels of management will be filled by Wheat executives. Although the headquarters will remain in <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, both Butcher and Wheat will maintain separate brokerage offices and none will close. Butcher said Wheat interests would own a majority of the combined companies. He also said <PERSON> Johannes </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuerst </PERSON> von Thurn und Taxis, a West German prince who bought one-third interest in Butcher last December, will be a minority owner in WFS. Under the terms of the arrangement, the companies will form <ORGANIZATION> WBF </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a financial services and investment banking holding company with two separate divisions. The company will have capital of $ 56 million, about $ 15 million contributed by Butcher & amp; Singer. WBF will be owned by the existing <ORGANIZATION> WSF </ORGANIZATION> Financial. The company will have about 2,000 employees, including 750 investment brokers in 92 locations from <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>.
